00:07:05.730 --> 00:07:07.460
For our organization
of our project,

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:10.530
we split up into backend
and frontend teams.

00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:12.630
The backend worked
on both the server

00:07:12.630 --> 00:07:15.730
and also the moderator interface
you saw here and to word cloud,

00:07:15.730 --> 00:07:16.230
for example.

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:22.370
This split was challenging
for new features,

00:07:22.370 --> 00:07:24.440
especially, because
features would

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:26.930
be interdependent or
frontend couldn't do anything

00:07:26.930 --> 00:07:28.475
until there was a backend.

00:07:28.475 --> 00:07:30.350
And there was a
communication gap throughout.

00:07:30.350 --> 00:07:32.260
When we needed to
add a new feature,

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:34.140
the API between the
backend and frontend

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:37.390
wasn't necessarily
well-documented.

00:07:37.390 --> 00:07:39.800
But overall, we think that
it led to simpler management

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:41.070
within the teams.

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:43.840
We didn't have a lot of
organization within each team.

00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:45.950
There wasn't a lot of
explicit organization.

00:07:45.950 --> 00:07:48.510
But it did help to know
that a smaller set of people

00:07:48.510 --> 00:07:50.468
would be working on the
frontend or the backend

00:07:50.468 --> 00:07:52.125
at any given time.

00:07:52.125 --> 00:07:54.625
In the future, I think we would
have gone even more specific

00:07:54.625 --> 00:07:55.514
in our roles.

00:07:55.514 --> 00:07:57.930
Like a few roles that we thought
would have been important

00:07:57.930 --> 00:07:59.420
include a UI designer.

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:03.090
This would have made sure that
UI design saw some first class

00:08:03.090 --> 00:08:06.250
love from the beginning
and would have made sure

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:09.997
that we actually focused
on UI from the beginning.

00:08:09.997 --> 00:08:12.330
It also would have helped to
have somebody communicating

00:08:12.330 --> 00:08:13.730
between the teams.

00:08:13.730 --> 00:08:16.160
This person may have
done some documentation

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:17.900
or may have simply
just made sure

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:20.150
that the frontend knew what
the backend was working on

00:08:20.150 --> 00:08:22.066
and the backend knew
what the frontend needed,

00:08:22.066 --> 00:08:25.010
so we could prioritize
well between the teams.

00:08:25.010 --> 00:08:26.760
It also would have
helped to have somebody

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:28.200
dedicated to paperwork.

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:30.950
This would have helped both
in submitting class paperwork

00:08:30.950 --> 00:08:33.179
and also just doing the
documentation that we needed,

00:08:33.179 --> 00:08:35.720
both for ourselves
and the class.

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:37.580
And finally, somebody
working on game design

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:41.020
would have helped us develop
more iterations early on

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:43.429
and think more about
the game aspects that

00:08:43.429 --> 00:08:45.670
go beyond what we already
knew the game would

00:08:45.670 --> 00:08:47.930
look like based on
the game of Snap

00:08:47.930 --> 00:08:49.055
we played from the clients.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:53.490
As far as technology
for our organization,

00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:56.120
we used Asana to
organize our tasks.

00:08:56.120 --> 00:08:57.947
Asana worked really well for us.

00:08:57.947 --> 00:09:00.530
In particular, it let us split
the task lists for the frontend

00:09:00.530 --> 00:09:01.250
and backend.

00:09:01.250 --> 00:09:03.250
This was useful, because
generally, the frontend

00:09:03.250 --> 00:09:07.560
didn't need to touch the
backend tasks and vice versa.

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:09.890
But on the other hand,
we had a hard time

00:09:09.890 --> 00:09:11.220
encoding task dependencies.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:13.690
This was particularly a
problem for a feature that

00:09:13.690 --> 00:09:15.700
crossed both the
backend and frontend,

00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:18.670
where some API was
needed on the backend

00:09:18.670 --> 00:09:21.790
and then was also
needed on the frontend.

00:09:21.790 --> 00:09:24.556
And you couldn't do
one without the other.

00:09:24.556 --> 00:09:26.880
We also had trouble
with task creation.

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:32.500
And this basically meant that
people didn't create tasks.

00:09:32.500 --> 00:09:35.070
And part of this was that we
didn't have a specific role

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:36.260
for creating the tasks.

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:38.530
And so, because of the
diffusion of responsibility,

00:09:38.530 --> 00:09:40.488
nobody would go through
and list out everything

00:09:40.488 --> 00:09:42.552
that needed to be done.

00:09:42.552 --> 00:09:44.010
To improve that in
the future, we'd

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:45.790
like to get people
more invested.

00:09:45.790 --> 00:09:48.910
Part of this was that people
had a lot of other classes.

00:09:48.910 --> 00:09:53.122
And it would have helped if
people both explicitly said

00:09:53.122 --> 00:09:55.080
how much they were going
to commit to the class

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:58.020
and also we made it
easier for people

00:09:58.020 --> 00:10:00.140
to contribute with the
small amount of time

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:02.355
that they had available.

