started the project,

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:36.990
we had this idea that people
would be represented as a car

00:12:36.990 --> 00:12:38.927
and they would be
racing other players.

00:12:38.927 --> 00:12:40.510
So we thought it
would be a great idea

00:12:40.510 --> 00:12:44.200
to use Phaser, which is a
sprite-based game framework.

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:48.175
But as you see here, we didn't
go through with the car idea.

00:12:48.175 --> 00:12:50.290
And we had no sprites.

00:12:50.290 --> 00:12:53.590
But we still used Phaser to
make this, our first design

00:12:53.590 --> 00:12:54.190
iteration.

00:12:54.190 --> 00:12:57.669
And we realized we didn't
really want that type of look

00:12:57.669 --> 00:12:58.210
for our game.

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:00.620
We needed something more
professional and more abstract

00:13:00.620 --> 00:13:03.810
that could be used in any
sort of setting that Pablo,

00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:05.570
our client, may use it.

00:13:05.570 --> 00:13:07.060
So we completely
scrapped Phaser.

00:13:07.060 --> 00:13:10.570
And we redid our
frontend design,

00:13:10.570 --> 00:13:15.180
deciding to just use
Bootstrap and CoffeeScript.

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:16.920
And this was our second design.

00:13:16.920 --> 00:13:21.990
As you can see here, it's just
very typical Bootstrap styling,

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:24.290
if you've ever used
Bootstrap before.

00:13:24.290 --> 00:13:26.920
So we tried to add a
little bit of flavor.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:29.680
And we also needed a better
way to kind of represent

00:13:29.680 --> 00:13:32.690
how the game is
progressing to the player.

00:13:32.690 --> 00:13:36.040
We currently had no idea
for that in this design.

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:38.050
So then we came up
with the final design

00:13:38.050 --> 00:13:42.320
that you guys played,
our theme of having blue.

00:13:42.320 --> 00:13:45.880
And then we created this
visualization to the right,

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:49.280
where each player is
represented by a dot.

00:13:49.280 --> 00:13:53.730
And snaps are represented by
lines being drawn to dots.

00:13:53.730 --> 00:13:55.250
And your height
is representative

00:13:55.250 --> 00:13:58.000
of your score in relation
to all the other players.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.750
So how we kind of got to
this final visualization idea

00:14:02.750 --> 00:14:04.560
was an interesting process.

00:14:04.560 --> 00:14:07.020
First, we thought it'd
be really cool to have

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:10.280
a word cloud on the frontend,
as well as the back end.

00:14:10.280 --> 00:14:12.640
But a player would only
be able to see the words

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:13.640
that they had submitted.

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:16.270
All the other words
would be blurred out.

00:14:16.270 --> 00:14:18.910
But this didn't really
convey to the player

00:14:18.910 --> 00:14:21.430
where they were in relation
to all the other players.

00:14:21.430 --> 00:14:24.240
So there wasn't any
sort of competitiveness.

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:28.970
So we came up with this
idea of having a race line,

00:14:28.970 --> 00:14:31.500
where all the players
would be on the line

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:36.320
and the height would represent
their score and their position.

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:38.740
And then we thought, well, we
can put these both together.

00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:40.500
But we investigated
the word cloud.

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:42.930
And we realized it'd be
extremely difficult to blur out

00:14:42.930 --> 00:14:43.900
these words.

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:47.150
And it wasn't really going to
be the best use of our time.

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:49.820
So then we came
up with this idea

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:51.880
of using dots to
represent players.

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:55.080
And we thought it'd be cool
if the size of your dot

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:56.570
represented your score.

00:14:56.570 --> 00:14:59.460
But the use case
for our application

00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:02.410
could involve 100
players or even more.

00:15:02.410 --> 00:15:05.760
So a lot of growing large dots
could really clutter our UI,

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:08.670
so we needed to rethink this.

00:15:08.670 --> 00:15:12.030
And this is when we finally
ended up deciding on height

00:15:12.030 --> 00:15:13.100
representing score.

00:15:15.770 --> 00:15:17.705
So I think we had really
good UI designers.

00:15:17.705 --> 00:15:18.830
And they were really quick.

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:21.090
Once we thought
of ideas, we were

00:15:21.090 --> 00:15:23.490
quick being able
to implement it.

00:15:23.490 --> 00:15:27.260
But the bad part was that we
were really late in coming up

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:28.850
with design decisions.

00:15:28.850 --> 00:15:30.320
We didn't start
thinking about how

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:33.180
we wanted to convey
the game to the player

00:15:33.180 --> 00:15:36.240
and how we wanted to make the
player feel about the game

00:15:36.240 --> 00:15:38.870
until really late
in the project.

00:15:38.870 --> 00:15:41.510
We focused more on what
the client needed as far

00:15:41.510 --> 00:15:44.440
as mechanics and not really
what the player was getting out

00:15:44.440 --> 00:15:45.890
of the game.

00:15:45.890 --> 00:15:47.440
So in the future,
definitely we need

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:50.280
to think about design
right from the get-go.

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:53.390
And we need to start prototyping
all the ideas that we have

00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:57.340
and testing them
out more thoroughly.

00:15:57.340 --> 00:16:00.730
TEJ CHAJED: So in summary,
the high points of our project

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:02.654
are that we did make
the client happy.

00:16:02.654 --> 00:16:04.820
And they've been using our
application and the game.

00:16:04.820 --> 00:16:06.650
And they really like the game.

00:16:06.650 --> 00:16:08.290
We're glad that
we focused on fun.

00:16:08.290 --> 00:16:09.840
The game has been
fun throughout.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:11.640
And players seem
to really enjoy it.

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:14.300
And I think maybe this is just
because of the core concept.

00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:17.260
And we're glad that, even though
this is an educational game,

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:21.100
it is intended for purposes
honestly of data collection,

00:16:21.100 --> 00:16:22.830
people really enjoy playing it.

00:16:22.830 --> 00:16:24.960
Unfortunately, we had
slow design iteration.

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:28.470
This prevented us from
really fully realizing

00:16:28.470 --> 00:16:30.580
all the ideas that we had
and figuring out which

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:33.354
one would be best for players.

00:16:33.354 --> 00:16:35.520
In the future, we'd like
to get people more invested

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:37.630
to try to solve these
issues and make sure

00:16:37.630 --> 00:16:40.970
that we best use
our time and create

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:42.935
the best product possible.

00:16:42.935 --> 00:16:44.435
And with that, we'll
take questions.

00:16:57.714 --> 00:17:02.026
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] Is there
a maximum number of players?

00:17:02.026 --> 00:17:04.230
TEJ CHAJED: We did
some stress tests

00:17:04.230 --> 00:17:06.710
to see how much the backend
on Heroku could support.

00:17:06.710 --> 00:17:13.050
And that seemed to work OK
up to 150 players or teams.

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:15.630
We are not really sure
what the frontend might

00:17:15.630 --> 00:17:17.783
look like at 150 real players.

00:17:17.783 --> 00:17:19.574
That might be actually
the limiting factor.

00:17:24.709 --> 00:17:27.150
AUDIENCE: Is that
150 people playing

00:17:27.150 --> 00:17:30.725
the same session or in the
multiple sessions 150 people?

00:17:30.725 --> 00:17:33.100
TEJ CHAJED: We currently don't
support multiple sessions.

00:17:33.100 --> 00:17:35.630
This is actually a request that
the client repeatedly gave us.

00:17:35.630 --> 00:17:37.463
But we thought that it
was just much simpler

00:17:37.463 --> 00:17:41.100
to avoid that for now, because
it wasn't strictly necessary.

00:17:41.100 --> 00:17:45.161
Most likely, the
load on the backend

00:17:45.161 --> 00:17:46.660
would be the same,
whether they were

00:17:46.660 --> 00:17:49.780
split into multiple sessions.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:52.660
But this is a solvable problem
by getting a beefier backend.

00:17:52.660 --> 00:17:54.157
AUDIENCE: I see.

00:17:54.157 --> 00:17:56.609
But right now, the backend
supports 150 people

00:17:56.609 --> 00:17:57.650
logged in simultaneously.

00:17:57.650 --> 00:17:59.510
TEJ CHAJED: About 150.

00:17:59.510 --> 00:18:02.249
We can obviously pay money
to get better servers

00:18:02.249 --> 00:18:03.415
and then run with many more.

00:18:03.415 --> 00:18:04.218
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:18:10.982 --> 00:18:12.815
TEJ CHAJED: Any questions
from the audience?

00:18:16.330 --> 00:18:21.040
AUDIENCE: So you got
some feedback from Pablo

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:23.630
specifically from the
