00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:30.140
And I'm wondering whether you
got any indication about what

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:34.544
the players felt outside of
this class plus your [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:34.544 --> 00:18:36.960
TEJ CHAJED: Sure, I think we
can both talk about our focus

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:40.379
tests, where we played with
players outside this class.

00:18:40.379 --> 00:18:42.420
SABRINA DRAMMIS: Yeah, so
one of the main things,

00:18:42.420 --> 00:18:46.230
I played with maybe a
group of at most 10 people.

00:18:46.230 --> 00:18:48.530
And they knew each
other, so they

00:18:48.530 --> 00:18:50.980
wanted to know who they
were snapping with.

00:18:50.980 --> 00:18:53.100
And they wanted to see
the names of all the dots,

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:56.080
so they could know
who they were beating

00:18:56.080 --> 00:18:58.030
or who they needed
to catch up to.

00:18:58.030 --> 00:19:02.201
But this would be unreasonable
in a large environment,

00:19:02.201 --> 00:19:04.200
especially when all the
people at the conference

00:19:04.200 --> 00:19:05.491
probably don't know each other.

00:19:05.491 --> 00:19:08.139
But I think that would be
a really cool thing to do,

00:19:08.139 --> 00:19:10.055
if we continued working
on this in the future.

00:19:10.055 --> 00:19:11.970
TEJ CHAJED: And I also
ran a similar test

00:19:11.970 --> 00:19:13.345
with people that
knew each other.

00:19:13.345 --> 00:19:15.664
And they actually used it
as part of their strategy.

00:19:15.664 --> 00:19:17.080
They knew what
other players would

00:19:17.080 --> 00:19:19.050
be submitting for that topic.

00:19:19.050 --> 00:19:22.700
And they could use that
to their advantage.

00:19:22.700 --> 00:19:25.011
So, for example, we did a
topic of systems papers.

00:19:25.011 --> 00:19:26.510
And we had a professor
in the group,

00:19:26.510 --> 00:19:30.150
so his paper showed up a bunch.

00:19:30.150 --> 00:19:34.420
And I would echo what Sabrina
said, that players really

00:19:34.420 --> 00:19:37.846
wanted more feedback
around the actual players

00:19:37.846 --> 00:19:39.720
in the game, which we
specifically didn't do,

00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:41.652
because the client didn't care.

00:19:41.652 --> 00:19:44.110
And in conferences, people
don't generally know each other.

00:19:44.110 --> 00:19:45.526
But I think that
if we were to use

00:19:45.526 --> 00:19:47.960
this as a more popular game,
then definitely focusing

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:50.670
on players and getting
more feedback, especially

00:19:50.670 --> 00:19:51.720
after the game is over.

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:53.803
People wanted to know who
they were snapping with.

00:19:53.803 --> 00:19:56.616
They wanted to see that graph,
all those lines overlaid,

00:19:56.616 --> 00:19:58.990
so they could see who they
were snapping with most often.

