And when you've lost two
toys, you lose the game.

00:27:14.370 --> 00:27:15.320
ANDREW: OK.

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:16.510
MATT: Thank you for playing.

00:27:21.319 --> 00:27:22.235
So that's Hello waves.

00:27:27.660 --> 00:27:35.560
So in our game, we had a
few challenges to overcome.

00:27:35.560 --> 00:27:39.060
The first was that
our game was based

00:27:39.060 --> 00:27:43.820
on forecast-based financing,
which is a very abstract topic.

00:27:43.820 --> 00:27:46.090
It's a pretty
understandable idea

00:27:46.090 --> 00:27:48.870
of using information about
the future and ideas of risk

00:27:48.870 --> 00:27:51.540
in order to decide where
to allocate resources.

00:27:51.540 --> 00:27:53.790
But it's still a bit abstract.

00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:57.706
And building a game around
it took a little bit of work.

00:27:57.706 --> 00:27:59.330
It's useful to note
that it's different

00:27:59.330 --> 00:28:00.420
than long-term planning.

00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:03.370
It's not just thinking about
what will happen in the future,

00:28:03.370 --> 00:28:06.410
building a dam to prevent
water or things like that.

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:09.000
And it's actually about
using the information

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.380
you have to make the
best decision for events

00:28:11.380 --> 00:28:15.750
that may be upcoming in
the semi-near future.

00:28:15.750 --> 00:28:17.730
We also wanted to avoid
making a game that

00:28:17.730 --> 00:28:21.340
was overly preachy or
simplified, where it was clear

00:28:21.340 --> 00:28:22.936
exactly how you're going to win.

00:28:22.936 --> 00:28:24.310
And you could just
basically push

00:28:24.310 --> 00:28:26.770
the forecast-based financing
button to win the game.

00:28:26.770 --> 00:28:28.860
We wanted players to
actually think and understand

00:28:28.860 --> 00:28:31.830
the concepts there,
instead of just coming up

00:28:31.830 --> 00:28:34.470
with the buzzword of
forecast-based financing.

00:28:34.470 --> 00:28:36.002
And finally, we
had the challenge

00:28:36.002 --> 00:28:38.460
of actually communicating that
forecast to players in a way

00:28:38.460 --> 00:28:40.010
that they would be
able to understand

00:28:40.010 --> 00:28:41.340
and then make use of.

00:28:41.340 --> 00:28:43.620
You could see in that game
that we had water levels

00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:45.130
and it would show on the map.

00:28:45.130 --> 00:28:47.640
And we found that players
were pretty good at using that

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.950
in order to make
decisions about what

00:28:49.950 --> 00:28:51.470
was going to happen
in the future

00:28:51.470 --> 00:28:53.294
and how to allocate
their resources.

00:28:53.294 --> 00:28:55.460
The other big challenge
that we had in the beginning

00:28:55.460 --> 00:28:59.310
was that our initial target
audience was policymakers.

00:28:59.310 --> 00:29:03.021
Like for Snap, Pablo had come in
and pitched us this game idea.

00:29:03.021 --> 00:29:05.020
And originally, he had
wanted us to build a game

00:29:05.020 --> 00:29:07.640
for policymakers that
would help them understand

00:29:07.640 --> 00:29:09.600
the benefits of
forecast-based financing

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:11.850
and, therefore, convince
them that they should develop

00:29:11.850 --> 00:29:15.240
policies that would give
resources to plans based

00:29:15.240 --> 00:29:17.770
on forecast-based financing.

00:29:17.770 --> 00:29:19.760
So I would like to take
you through a couple

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:22.720
of our prototypes just to show
you the evolution and comment

00:29:22.720 --> 00:29:26.570
sort of on our process.

00:29:26.570 --> 00:29:31.300
Actually, to preface that,
we had a lot of prototypes,

00:29:31.300 --> 00:29:33.310
because of our idea
was so abstract

00:29:33.310 --> 00:29:35.910
and because we weren't sure
how to address our audience.

00:29:35.910 --> 00:29:38.670
So we built a lot of
prototypes to start with.

00:29:38.670 --> 00:29:42.454
We had ideas that ranged
across sort of levels of scope

00:29:42.454 --> 00:29:44.870
of what you controlled, where
you controlled entire cities

00:29:44.870 --> 00:29:46.619
or where you controlled
individual workers

00:29:46.619 --> 00:29:47.780
and moved them around.

00:29:47.780 --> 00:29:49.540
And then we would pull from
all these different kinds

00:29:49.540 --> 00:29:51.800
of ideas what worked, what
didn't, what did people

00:29:51.800 --> 00:29:53.760
understand, what confused them.

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:55.820
And from that, we got
a really good idea

00:29:55.820 --> 00:29:58.660
of what concepts helped
people understand the idea

00:29:58.660 --> 00:30:02.710
and brought them into this final
game that we ended up with.

00:30:02.710 --> 00:30:05.530
So the project
started on October 15.

00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:07.110
And this was our
first prototype.

00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:09.210
It was a terminal-based
game, where

00:30:09.210 --> 00:30:12.330
you had some kind of information
about a future rainfall.

00:30:12.330 --> 00:30:15.140
And then you had to type in your
commands of how you controlled

00:30:15.140 --> 00:30:16.900
different cities.

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:19.720
This, actually,
people found it fun.

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:22.410
But as you might expect, the
feedback wasn't very good.

00:30:22.410 --> 00:30:24.220
And people didn't
quite understand

00:30:24.220 --> 00:30:26.510
how to move forward with it.

00:30:26.510 --> 00:30:29.110
It put a lot of
cognitive load on people.

00:30:29.110 --> 00:30:31.340
So when we moved
forward, we tried

00:30:31.340 --> 00:30:35.660
to give people more easily
understandable actions to use.

00:30:35.660 --> 00:30:38.710
But the problem with this game
was that it was time based

00:30:38.710 --> 00:30:39.940
and it updated every second.

00:30:39.940 --> 00:30:41.815
And so there are so
numbers flying at people,

00:30:41.815 --> 00:30:44.690
like even MIT students who play
tested it couldn't understand.

00:30:44.690 --> 00:30:46.920
So we figured that
people like policymakers,

00:30:46.920 --> 00:30:48.880
who didn't have much
experience with games,

00:30:48.880 --> 00:30:51.590
really wouldn't be able to
understand the game at all.

00:30:51.590 --> 00:30:53.930
So instead, we
went to turn based.

00:30:53.930 --> 00:30:55.260
And that helped.

00:30:55.260 --> 00:30:58.730
But at the same time, it's
tough to see on this projector,

00:30:58.730 --> 00:31:00.560
but we have a forecast
underneath that says

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:02.260
how much rainfall is expected.

00:31:02.260 --> 00:31:04.260
And again, that wasn't
understandable to people,

00:31:04.260 --> 00:31:06.843
because they couldn't understand
what three inches of rainfall

00:31:06.843 --> 00:31:08.029
meant for their city.

00:31:08.029 --> 00:31:10.070
And they couldn't understand
how that contributed

00:31:10.070 --> 00:31:11.652
to a possible disaster.

00:31:11.652 --> 00:31:13.610
At this point, Pablo
actually came by the class

00:31:13.610 --> 00:31:14.900
and played the game.

00:31:14.900 --> 00:31:17.270
And then he told us
that he wasn't even sure

00:31:17.270 --> 00:31:19.300
that he could get
policymakers to play the game,

00:31:19.300 --> 00:31:21.090
because they may not
have enough time.

00:31:21.090 --> 00:31:23.789
Instead, he wanted us to
switch to grade schoolers,

00:31:23.789 --> 00:31:25.330
because we could
teach them something

00:31:25.330 --> 00:31:27.660
about forecast-based financing
and help them understand

00:31:27.660 --> 00:31:30.052
as they grew up.

00:31:30.052 --> 00:31:31.760
And this was great
for us, because making

00:31:31.760 --> 00:31:34.230
a game that was serious,
easy for somebody

00:31:34.230 --> 00:31:36.770
who didn't have experience
with games to play, and also

00:31:36.770 --> 00:31:40.680
fun and engaging was too
difficult for us actually.

00:31:40.680 --> 00:31:43.930
So moving to grade
schoolers was awesome.

00:31:43.930 --> 00:31:48.310
He also suggested that we try
to make the idea of rainfall

00:31:48.310 --> 00:31:50.990
or water levels more visceral.

00:31:50.990 --> 00:31:54.450
And that's when we came upon
this idea of the rising waters.

00:31:54.450 --> 00:31:56.830
Whenever players looked
at this, they instantly

00:31:56.830 --> 00:31:58.480
understood the
concept of the game.

00:31:58.480 --> 00:32:00.150
The feedback might not be there.

00:32:00.150 --> 00:32:02.710
The beautiful UI
might not be there.

00:32:02.710 --> 00:32:05.020
But the idea of having
cities with workers in them

00:32:05.020 --> 00:32:07.890
and a rising water level
coming towards them, everybody

00:32:07.890 --> 00:32:08.800
understood that.

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:10.425
And it made it a lot
easier for players

00:32:10.425 --> 00:32:12.220
to reason about the game.

00:32:12.220 --> 00:32:15.170
From there, we added things
like nicer art, better feedback,

00:32:15.170 --> 00:32:18.770
which you can't quite see
in the static picture, more

00:32:18.770 --> 00:32:21.300
improvements to how
the forecast worked.

00:32:21.300 --> 00:32:27.740
And eventually, we ended up
with our final version today.

00:32:27.740 --> 00:32:31.180
NORMAN: So to talk a little bit
about our actual development

00:32:31.180 --> 00:32:33.820
process, so our team was
structured into three

00:32:33.820 --> 00:32:36.270
main subteams, production,
which was in charge

00:32:36.270 --> 00:32:39.700
of managerial roles,
deliverables, and play testing,

00:32:39.700 --> 00:32:44.260
and so there was a shared
responsibility there;

00:32:44.260 --> 00:32:45.900
technical team,
which was in charge

00:32:45.900 --> 00:32:49.450
of the bulk of the coding
work; and a user experience

00:32:49.450 --> 00:32:52.910
team, which would be in charge
of assets, UI design, and UI

00:32:52.910 --> 00:32:54.260
design.

00:32:54.260 --> 00:32:57.750
We also initially
envisioned subteam leaders,

00:32:57.750 --> 00:33:00.460
where we'd be kind of
communicating through them.

00:33:00.460 --> 00:33:02.450
But we found the concept
kind of redundant.

00:33:02.450 --> 00:33:05.420
And so we've worked pretty
much with like a flat structure

00:33:05.420 --> 00:33:08.570
between the three teams.

00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:12.140
So from the beginning,
we encouraged good coding

00:33:12.140 --> 00:33:12.640
practice.

00:33:12.640 --> 00:33:16.430
And so we used good
tools available to us.

00:33:16.430 --> 00:33:19.470
One of these is Yeoman, which
is a JavaScript scaffolding

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:21.470
framework.

00:33:21.470 --> 00:33:24.890
And this helped us out a
lot by basically automating

00:33:24.890 --> 00:33:29.670
a lot of our JavaScript tasks
and making our code modular.

00:33:29.670 --> 00:33:32.780
We also used Phaser
state machine,

00:33:32.780 --> 00:33:37.430
which is this kind of badly
documented new feature

00:33:37.430 --> 00:33:40.380
in the Phaser game engine,
which was the JavaScript game

00:33:40.380 --> 00:33:42.940
engine that we used.

00:33:42.940 --> 00:33:45.730
It's a bit badly documented.

00:33:45.730 --> 00:33:47.520
But it did save us
a lot of headaches.

00:33:47.520 --> 00:33:51.200
And once we figured that out,
that proved immensely helpful.

00:33:51.200 --> 00:33:57.240
And we also used MVC, which is
a computer software engineering

00:33:57.240 --> 00:33:59.810
term standing for
Model View Controller.

00:33:59.810 --> 00:34:03.360
And again, by encouraging
these good coding practices,

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:06.940
we reduced dependencies and
made sure that our team was

00:34:06.940 --> 00:34:09.120
productive.

00:34:09.120 --> 00:34:12.480
In terms of communication,
we also, similar to Snap,

00:34:12.480 --> 00:34:15.150
used Slack, which is kind of
like a modernized chatrooms.

00:34:15.150 --> 00:34:16.860
It's very feature rich.

00:34:16.860 --> 00:34:20.360
And so you can share files,
channels, and things like that.

00:34:20.360 --> 00:34:23.870
And we also use the
idea of the Daily Scrum.

00:34:23.870 --> 00:34:26.070
We implemented it in class.

00:34:26.070 --> 00:34:29.219
And we would say what we
had done that class, what

00:34:29.219 --> 00:34:35.300
we would be doing, and what we
wanted to do until next class.

00:34:35.300 --> 00:34:38.560
And so now, the major
challenges that we

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:41.860
faced during the development
process though where

00:34:41.860 --> 00:34:44.960
that our team members came
from very different backgrounds

00:34:44.960 --> 00:34:47.679
and had very different
preferences about games.

00:34:47.679 --> 00:34:51.679
Some of our team members are
very hardcore StarCraft players

00:34:51.679 --> 00:34:55.980
and very good at RTS games,
while other members of our team

00:34:55.980 --> 00:34:59.920
preferred like a more laid
back mobile game Fruit Ninja

00:34:59.920 --> 00:35:01.120
kind of approach.

00:35:01.120 --> 00:35:04.040
And so trying to mediate
those two viewpoints

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:06.650
and trying to create
a game that would

00:35:06.650 --> 00:35:11.550
engage both types of
gamers was a challenge

00:35:11.550 --> 00:35:14.660
that we had to overcome.

00:35:14.660 --> 00:35:18.000
And so another big challenge
that we had in our development

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.105
process, as you saw
through our progression

00:35:22.105 --> 00:35:23.480
through our
different prototypes,

00:35:23.480 --> 00:35:27.640
was that our direction was not
very clear, until about halfway

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:28.930
through the project.

00:35:28.930 --> 00:35:32.630
And so partially because we
had different ideas on what

00:35:32.630 --> 00:35:36.020
the game should look like and
also partially because we had

00:35:36.020 --> 00:35:38.670
such an abstract idea of
forecast-based financing

00:35:38.670 --> 00:35:43.890
that even we didn't have that
good of a grasp on initially,

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:46.220
it took us a while
to really get settled

00:35:46.220 --> 00:35:47.880
on what we wanted to build.

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:52.400
And so this really challenged
our development process

00:35:52.400 --> 00:35:58.340
and made us have to build a
lot before we got something

00:35:58.340 --> 00:36:01.120
that we liked.

00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:04.390
And so eventually,
we did end up having

00:36:04.390 --> 00:36:07.690
to cut some features
of like multiple levels

00:36:07.690 --> 00:36:10.670
or like a guided
tutorial for the player.

00:36:10.670 --> 00:36:14.500
We thought that this would
introduce too much new content

00:36:14.500 --> 00:36:19.700
that would need to be play
tested, balanced, and tested

00:36:19.700 --> 00:36:22.420
to ensure consistency with
the rest of our game, which

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:24.320
we viewed as taking
up too much time.

00:36:24.320 --> 00:36:28.660
And we also cut the idea of
adding more individuality

00:36:28.660 --> 00:36:32.270
to the workers or to
the toys that you saw,

00:36:32.270 --> 00:36:34.150
other than different
graphics for each.

00:36:37.830 --> 00:36:40.647
MATT: Some of the worst
things that we did on our team

00:36:40.647 --> 00:36:42.230
is that we spent a
lot of time on work

00:36:42.230 --> 00:36:44.150
that got thrown out entirely.

00:36:44.150 --> 00:36:47.420
All the prototypes we did, they
were actually pretty useful,

00:36:47.420 --> 00:36:50.420
because of the things we learned
about the concept and about

00:36:50.420 --> 00:36:52.070
how people would play the game.

00:36:52.070 --> 00:36:53.920
But we did spend a
lot of time on things

00:36:53.920 --> 00:36:57.420
like art or nitty gritty
details that didn't really

00:36:57.420 --> 00:36:59.670
need to be figured out and
that we could have put off

00:36:59.670 --> 00:37:02.320
until later in the project.

00:37:02.320 --> 00:37:06.640
We also kept the game direction
too vague for too long.

00:37:06.640 --> 00:37:09.630
As Norman said, we spent
a lot of time with that.

00:37:09.630 --> 00:37:12.800
And it probably ate up
too much of our time.

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:14.780
Although it helped
us learn, we could

00:37:14.780 --> 00:37:16.650
have moved faster
in the beginning

00:37:16.650 --> 00:37:18.120
to get to a solid idea.

00:37:18.120 --> 00:37:21.670
Because once we got to a solid
idea of the rising waters,

00:37:21.670 --> 00:37:24.170
our team started to
centralize around it

00:37:24.170 --> 00:37:26.730
a lot better, because
we could actually

00:37:26.730 --> 00:37:27.970
deal with something concrete.

00:37:27.970 --> 00:37:30.030
While we were dealing
with the abstract ideas,

00:37:30.030 --> 00:37:32.540
everybody was all over the
place and arguing about things

00:37:32.540 --> 00:37:35.040
that didn't quite line up.

00:37:35.040 --> 00:37:38.430
And the worst decision of
all that we started with

00:37:38.430 --> 00:37:41.200
and that sort of made the
problem of going too vague

00:37:41.200 --> 00:37:42.791
and all these
other things happen

00:37:42.791 --> 00:37:44.290
is that we were
originally thinking,

00:37:44.290 --> 00:37:48.030
how do we skin forecast
based financing as a game?

00:37:48.030 --> 00:37:50.690
How do we take this
idea of using forecast

00:37:50.690 --> 00:37:54.210
to make decisions and
then just gamify it,

00:37:54.210 --> 00:37:57.650
which we eventually
realized wasn't fun

00:37:57.650 --> 00:38:00.557
and didn't help us actually
come up with any ideas.

00:38:00.557 --> 00:38:02.140
Instead when we
flipped it and started

00:38:02.140 --> 00:38:05.260
talking about what game
could we create and use

00:38:05.260 --> 00:38:09.140
forecast-based financing to
improve it and teach players

00:38:09.140 --> 00:38:12.390
how to play the game and,
therefore, allow them to come

00:38:12.390 --> 00:38:15.220
out of the game, having learned
about forecast-based financing,

00:38:15.220 --> 00:38:16.530
the world sort of opened up.

00:38:16.530 --> 00:38:18.238
Everything became a
lot more interesting.

00:38:18.238 --> 00:38:21.892
And we found that we
started to move faster.

00:38:21.892 --> 00:38:24.350
Some of the best decisions that
we made, on the other hand,

00:38:24.350 --> 00:38:26.520
as Norman said,
we had good tools,

00:38:26.520 --> 00:38:29.610
which meant that even when
we threw out prototypes,

00:38:29.610 --> 00:38:33.020
although we wasted things
like art resources and things

00:38:33.020 --> 00:38:36.350
like that, we actually didn't
end up wasting very much code,

00:38:36.350 --> 00:38:39.000
because things like the
idea of workers or cities

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.500
could literally be pulled
out of the old games we had,

00:38:41.500 --> 00:38:43.870
put into our new game,
and then reworked

00:38:43.870 --> 00:38:47.670
to build our new structure.

00:38:47.670 --> 00:38:49.510
We also weren't afraid
to trust each other

00:38:49.510 --> 00:38:52.210
and throw out the
things that didn't work.

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:53.890
Once we started
moving fast, we had

00:38:53.890 --> 00:38:55.575
a lot of ideas that
would come out,

00:38:55.575 --> 00:38:57.680
and we would say, OK,
this doesn't work.

00:38:57.680 --> 00:38:59.290
We're actually
going to scrap it.

00:38:59.290 --> 00:39:03.210
Or we think that this isn't
the direction we need to go in.

00:39:03.210 --> 00:39:06.641
And everybody was willing
to go along with it.

00:39:06.641 --> 00:39:08.890
It's not a good feeling to
see your things thrown out.

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:11.310
But everybody understood that
was for the best of the game.

00:39:11.310 --> 00:39:13.768
And I really appreciate their
understanding with everything

00:39:13.768 --> 00:39:14.710
too.

00:39:14.710 --> 00:39:16.710
And part of that all
comes down to the fact

00:39:16.710 --> 00:39:18.900
that we were on board
with our final idea.

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:21.465
We were all excited about
the concept that we had.

00:39:21.465 --> 00:39:23.090
Part of that might
have been the relief

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:24.881
of coming to a concrete
idea after spending

00:39:24.881 --> 00:39:26.330
so much time being vague.

00:39:26.330 --> 00:39:28.080
But once we had
the concrete idea,

00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:32.120
we really moved fast and
worked well around it.

00:39:32.120 --> 00:39:33.875
So thank you and any questions.

