00:44:53.548 --> 00:44:55.640
MIRIAM: Hello, my
name is Miriam.

00:44:55.640 --> 00:44:58.460
And today, I'm going to be
presenting for Team Heat Wave.

00:44:58.460 --> 00:45:01.110
And we made a game
called Heat Wave.

00:45:01.110 --> 00:45:05.600
So the goal of Heat
Wave was and is

00:45:05.600 --> 00:45:08.370
to educate Red Cross
workers about how to prepare

00:45:08.370 --> 00:45:10.360
for and handle heat waves.

00:45:10.360 --> 00:45:12.270
And if you've never been
through a heat wave,

00:45:12.270 --> 00:45:15.220
it's just defined as
elevated temperatures

00:45:15.220 --> 00:45:16.790
for an extended period of time.

00:45:16.790 --> 00:45:18.440
And the way you
prepare for that is you

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:20.330
set up umbrellas for shade.

00:45:20.330 --> 00:45:21.600
You get water coolers.

00:45:21.600 --> 00:45:23.220
And during the
actual event, you try

00:45:23.220 --> 00:45:26.830
to go inside and drink an
excess amount of water.

00:45:26.830 --> 00:45:29.120
So while we had that
game goal, we also

00:45:29.120 --> 00:45:34.220
had design goals of usability,
playability, and education--

00:45:34.220 --> 00:45:36.360
usability because if
the game doesn't open,

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:38.320
it doesn't turn on,
that's a problem,

00:45:38.320 --> 00:45:40.531
it doesn't work, playability
because we wanted people

00:45:40.531 --> 00:45:42.280
to be able to play
through the whole game,

00:45:42.280 --> 00:45:46.460
it's just very fundamental,
and education because this game

00:45:46.460 --> 00:45:49.310
is meant to educate Red
Cross workers about how

00:45:49.310 --> 00:45:50.340
to deal with heat waves.

00:45:50.340 --> 00:45:53.050
So we really wanted that to be
one of our primary objectives

00:45:53.050 --> 00:45:55.240
for the game.

00:45:55.240 --> 00:45:59.680
So to meet these goals, we
had our design processes.

00:45:59.680 --> 00:46:01.410
And I'll talk a
little bit about each

00:46:01.410 --> 00:46:03.220
of these in detail in a minute.

00:46:03.220 --> 00:46:05.400
But we started off
just as the other teams

00:46:05.400 --> 00:46:06.850
did with brainstorming.

00:46:06.850 --> 00:46:10.380
Then we formed a team
based off of our ideas.

00:46:10.380 --> 00:46:12.880
And then we broke
down responsibility.

00:46:12.880 --> 00:46:16.080
So one person was in charge
of one aspect of the game.

00:46:16.080 --> 00:46:18.320
Another was in charge
of like the graphics,

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:19.430
all separate tasks.

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:21.030
And then we
continuously updated.

00:46:21.030 --> 00:46:23.970
And what we used for that
was Trello, primarily.

00:46:23.970 --> 00:46:25.720
And I'll talk more
about that in a minute.

00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:27.300
So brainstorming,
we were actually

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:31.000
right there on the board
drawing things for a while.

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:34.800
And we had two major ideas
going as a group of people

00:46:34.800 --> 00:46:36.840
just considering this topic.

00:46:36.840 --> 00:46:39.340
The two ideas we had were the
game we actually came up with,

00:46:39.340 --> 00:46:43.490
where you play as a Red Cross
worker trying to help people.

00:46:43.490 --> 00:46:47.440
And then our second game
was playing as a heat wave,

00:46:47.440 --> 00:46:49.910
trying to make people faint.

00:46:49.910 --> 00:46:52.050
And while that actually
sounds like a lot of fun,

00:46:52.050 --> 00:46:53.524
we stuck with the first idea.

00:46:53.524 --> 00:46:55.190
And the reason we did
that is we thought

00:46:55.190 --> 00:46:57.490
we could get more
education into the game.

00:46:57.490 --> 00:47:00.760
Because education was such
a primary focus for us,

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:03.547
we really wanted it to be
the core basis of the game.

00:47:03.547 --> 00:47:05.380
So we went with the
game that would directly

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:07.470
correlate to what these
Red Cross workers would

00:47:07.470 --> 00:47:11.350
be doing out in the streets
before and during a heat wave.

00:47:11.350 --> 00:47:13.700
And based off of that
idea, we formed a team.

00:47:13.700 --> 00:47:15.480
We actually had a
pretty large team.

00:47:15.480 --> 00:47:17.339
This is eight out of
nine of our people.

00:47:17.339 --> 00:47:19.380
Joe wasn't in this photo,
because he wasn't there

00:47:19.380 --> 00:47:20.010
that day.

00:47:20.010 --> 00:47:21.301
But we had a really large team.

00:47:21.301 --> 00:47:24.859
So we had to be really focused
as to like who was doing what

00:47:24.859 --> 00:47:26.150
and what was getting done when.

00:47:26.150 --> 00:47:27.816
Because when you have
such a large team,

00:47:27.816 --> 00:47:29.910
things can slip
through the cracks.

00:47:29.910 --> 00:47:31.840
So we used Scrum.

00:47:31.840 --> 00:47:34.740
And as you can see up there,
it says so many emails,

00:47:34.740 --> 00:47:38.250
because there were
so many emails.

00:47:38.250 --> 00:47:41.600
But the way we dealt with that
based off of previous projects

00:47:41.600 --> 00:47:43.850
was to say, well, we're going
to have a lot of emails.

00:47:43.850 --> 00:47:45.440
There's nothing we
can do about that.

00:47:45.440 --> 00:47:48.010
But we can make the
emails relevant,

00:47:48.010 --> 00:47:50.520
so we can break them
into different threads.

00:47:50.520 --> 00:47:54.327
So the people who were
handling the character objects,

00:47:54.327 --> 00:47:56.160
they're just going to
have their own thread.

00:47:56.160 --> 00:47:59.270
And maybe like one person who's
communicating between teams

00:47:59.270 --> 00:48:00.740
will also be on that thread.

00:48:00.740 --> 00:48:02.320
But it's really their thread.

00:48:02.320 --> 00:48:03.450
So we had a lot of emails.

00:48:03.450 --> 00:48:06.190
But they were divided up
as to who got to see them

00:48:06.190 --> 00:48:08.061
and who it affected.

00:48:08.061 --> 00:48:10.060
And the other thing we
did is we had our Trello.

00:48:10.060 --> 00:48:12.152
And we constantly updated that.

00:48:12.152 --> 00:48:13.610
And we kept track
of what was being

00:48:13.610 --> 00:48:15.960
done in this sprint
and previous sprints.

00:48:15.960 --> 00:48:17.520
And it was really
easy to see what

00:48:17.520 --> 00:48:19.150
was taking longer
than we expected

00:48:19.150 --> 00:48:22.805
and what was done, what was
done but could use improvements.

00:48:22.805 --> 00:48:23.930
Like you could make a note.

00:48:23.930 --> 00:48:26.080
We had like a
not-done-yet section.

00:48:26.080 --> 00:48:28.840
So we really managed to
stay organized that way.

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:31.220
And the other thing we
did to make sure things

00:48:31.220 --> 00:48:32.650
got done was group meetings.

00:48:32.650 --> 00:48:35.140
And these were quintessential
for our groups.

00:48:35.140 --> 00:48:37.890
We had a bunch of like
three-hour long meetings.

00:48:37.890 --> 00:48:40.250
And we would get
task after task done,

00:48:40.250 --> 00:48:43.180
bug after bug fixed,
and really just worked

00:48:43.180 --> 00:48:46.490
through for hours on end.

00:48:46.490 --> 00:48:49.380
So once we had this game and
we were all working on it,

00:48:49.380 --> 00:48:52.180
we had four focus
tests that we ran.

00:48:52.180 --> 00:48:53.790
And they all had a theme.

00:48:53.790 --> 00:48:57.210
So our first focus test
was about the concept,

00:48:57.210 --> 00:49:01.650
can we educate people in
the basic mechanic of that

00:49:01.650 --> 00:49:04.220
we think we're going to use.

00:49:04.220 --> 00:49:05.780
And I'll talk about
that in a minute.

00:49:05.780 --> 00:49:07.363
The second one was
overarching issues.

00:49:07.363 --> 00:49:10.940
So I said our three design goals
were usability, playability,

00:49:10.940 --> 00:49:11.740
and education.

00:49:11.740 --> 00:49:13.860
So that was really our
second focus assessed.

00:49:13.860 --> 00:49:16.010
The third focus
test was visuals.

00:49:16.010 --> 00:49:17.650
Are we connecting with the user?

00:49:17.650 --> 00:49:19.620
Are these the visuals
we want to have?

00:49:19.620 --> 00:49:22.330
And then for the fourth
one was game balancing.

00:49:22.330 --> 00:49:25.140
Does this game feel fun to play?

00:49:25.140 --> 00:49:26.680
Is it working out?

00:49:26.680 --> 00:49:28.770
So the first focus
test, we focused

00:49:28.770 --> 00:49:31.050
on the general mechanics.

00:49:31.050 --> 00:49:35.170
We had a low fidelity
prototype, which is actually

00:49:35.170 --> 00:49:36.610
a Python-based game.

00:49:36.610 --> 00:49:37.940
And there was a list of people.

00:49:37.940 --> 00:49:40.370
And you could say, I want
to talk to this person based

00:49:40.370 --> 00:49:43.780
on some attributes and
offer them water, tell them

00:49:43.780 --> 00:49:45.010
to go inside.

00:49:45.010 --> 00:49:47.600
And each turn, you could either
continue talking to them,

00:49:47.600 --> 00:49:49.680
say forget it, you're
being annoying,

00:49:49.680 --> 00:49:51.390
or oh, you accepted
water, I'm going

00:49:51.390 --> 00:49:52.639
to move on to the next person.

00:49:52.639 --> 00:49:54.150
Or you could do nothing.

00:49:54.150 --> 00:49:57.920
And what we learned very
quickly was that it was working.

00:49:57.920 --> 00:49:59.850
People were choosing
to try and help

00:49:59.850 --> 00:50:01.410
people based on
their characteristics

00:50:01.410 --> 00:50:04.810
and based on oh, well, this
person fainted really quickly,

00:50:04.810 --> 00:50:07.310
and they were homeless,
so I think homeless people

00:50:07.310 --> 00:50:08.150
might faint faster.

00:50:08.150 --> 00:50:10.066
Though actually, I don't
think homeless people

00:50:10.066 --> 00:50:10.847
were in this game.

00:50:10.847 --> 00:50:13.305
And we also experimented with
different types of dialogues.

00:50:13.305 --> 00:50:16.300
So we experimented with having
like very factual dialogue,

00:50:16.300 --> 00:50:18.000
drinking water is
really important,

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:21.190
even if you're not too
thirsty versus something like,

00:50:21.190 --> 00:50:23.990
hide your wife, hide
your kids heat wave.

00:50:23.990 --> 00:50:27.830
So once we had that
general concept in place,

00:50:27.830 --> 00:50:30.850
we built a basic unit game.

00:50:30.850 --> 00:50:32.770
And we wanted to see
overarching issues.

00:50:32.770 --> 00:50:35.580
So we had these
four-- well five,

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:38.160
but one person has already
fainted in this picture-- five

00:50:38.160 --> 00:50:40.649
different characters with
different attributes.

00:50:40.649 --> 00:50:42.190
And you could choose
to talk to them.

00:50:42.190 --> 00:50:44.390
It was the same
exact concept we had

00:50:44.390 --> 00:50:46.760
in the Python text-based game.

00:50:46.760 --> 00:50:48.770
This time, it was a
little more visual.

00:50:48.770 --> 00:50:52.040
There were people and there was
a dialogue that would show up.

00:50:52.040 --> 00:50:55.550
But it wasn't fully there yet.

00:50:55.550 --> 00:50:59.470
And what we saw was the
usability and the playability

00:50:59.470 --> 00:51:01.770
were definitely
having issues here.

00:51:01.770 --> 00:51:02.945
You can see that.

00:51:02.945 --> 00:51:05.070
But the education was
definitely coming through it.

00:51:05.070 --> 00:51:07.522
In fact, people wanted
it to be more visual.

00:51:07.522 --> 00:51:08.980
And we saw that,
and we said, well,

00:51:08.980 --> 00:51:11.060
we have to test more visuals.

00:51:11.060 --> 00:51:14.600
So you can see, this was
the version we tested later.

00:51:14.600 --> 00:51:17.392
And we said, how is
this working, who

00:51:17.392 --> 00:51:18.600
are you choosing to click on?

00:51:18.600 --> 00:51:21.309
And people said, well, first
of all, it's confusing.

00:51:21.309 --> 00:51:22.600
All these people look the same.

00:51:22.600 --> 00:51:26.210
I can kind of tell who's a
woman and who might be a man,

00:51:26.210 --> 00:51:27.242
but that's about it.

00:51:27.242 --> 00:51:28.950
The labels aren't
moving with the people.

00:51:28.950 --> 00:51:30.500
Even if they were
moving with the people,

00:51:30.500 --> 00:51:31.541
they're really too small.

00:51:31.541 --> 00:51:32.850
We can't tell who's who.

00:51:32.850 --> 00:51:35.025
And we said, well,
we have this art

00:51:35.025 --> 00:51:36.400
that we think
we're going to redo

00:51:36.400 --> 00:51:37.590
all the art in the style of.

00:51:37.590 --> 00:51:39.470
We're thinking about
getting rid of the labels.

00:51:39.470 --> 00:51:40.310
Do you think that's a good idea?

00:51:40.310 --> 00:51:42.059
And they said, yes,
get rid of the labels.

00:51:42.059 --> 00:51:43.320
They're too small anyway.

00:51:43.320 --> 00:51:45.402
And so we showed them
this caricature of one

00:51:45.402 --> 00:51:47.860
of the types of the characters,
which is a homeless person.

00:51:47.860 --> 00:51:51.010
They're a very vulnerable
group to heat waves.

00:51:51.010 --> 00:51:53.570
We said, this is kind of the
art style we were looking at.

00:51:53.570 --> 00:51:54.840
We think it displays
more information.

00:51:54.840 --> 00:51:55.881
Do you think that's good?

00:51:55.881 --> 00:51:58.370
And we got enormously
positive feedback on that.

00:51:58.370 --> 00:52:00.810
They say, definitely, I
would click on this guy,

00:52:00.810 --> 00:52:02.310
because he looks
like he needs help.

00:52:02.310 --> 00:52:04.444
And you'll see that later.

00:52:04.444 --> 00:52:06.610
Something else we were
having an issue with visually

00:52:06.610 --> 00:52:08.940
was that the way
people would go inside

00:52:08.940 --> 00:52:12.080
is they would just
kind of wander out.

00:52:12.080 --> 00:52:14.690
But the way they fainted, they
would actually just disappear,

00:52:14.690 --> 00:52:15.860
proof.

00:52:15.860 --> 00:52:18.335
So people didn't
notice it actually.

00:52:18.335 --> 00:52:19.960
And then they'd
suddenly be like, well,

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:21.590
there was 10 people,
and now there's

00:52:21.590 --> 00:52:24.330
five people, and what happened?

00:52:24.330 --> 00:52:27.280
So we said, OK, we
know this is an issue.

00:52:27.280 --> 00:52:30.220
What do you think would be
the best way to visually show

00:52:30.220 --> 00:52:32.631
that people are fainting
and that would emotionally

00:52:32.631 --> 00:52:33.380
resonate with you?

00:52:33.380 --> 00:52:35.338
And they said, well, we
want them to fall over.

00:52:35.338 --> 00:52:37.790
And maybe it'd be nice if
there were some other feedback,

00:52:37.790 --> 00:52:39.810
like sound or something.

00:52:39.810 --> 00:52:42.220
And we said, OK, we'll
take that a step farther.

00:52:42.220 --> 00:52:43.890
And we did.

00:52:43.890 --> 00:52:46.300
And we'll talk about that later.

00:52:46.300 --> 00:52:47.850
And the third thing
that we really

00:52:47.850 --> 00:52:51.410
got back from this visual
feedback focus test

00:52:51.410 --> 00:52:54.230
was that there was no indication
when people were getting sick.

00:52:54.230 --> 00:52:56.830
So in the real world,
if you're getting sick,

00:52:56.830 --> 00:53:00.500
you might like turned
red, get really sweaty.

00:53:00.500 --> 00:53:03.880
If you're about to faint, it'll
be very obvious is the point.

00:53:03.880 --> 00:53:05.260
And there was no
indication here.

00:53:05.260 --> 00:53:07.080
So we said, well, we're going
to do something about it.

00:53:07.080 --> 00:53:08.310
We're going to put that
on the back burner,

00:53:08.310 --> 00:53:09.320
keep thinking about it.

00:53:09.320 --> 00:53:12.010
And we are going to
fix that somehow.

00:53:12.010 --> 00:53:14.300
And so we put that
all into practice.

00:53:14.300 --> 00:53:16.180
And you'll see the
screens in a bit.

00:53:16.180 --> 00:53:20.070
But our final focus test, we
focused on game balancing.

00:53:20.070 --> 00:53:21.390
Is this game balanced?

00:53:21.390 --> 00:53:23.470
Are people fainting
at a reasonable rate?

00:53:23.470 --> 00:53:24.980
The problem was
that we would have

00:53:24.980 --> 00:53:27.340
like six people all
fainting at the same time.

00:53:27.340 --> 00:53:31.680
They said no, they have to
faint at different increments.

00:53:31.680 --> 00:53:33.510
And also on top of
that, we had an issue

00:53:33.510 --> 00:53:36.170
where the temperature
was somewhat random,

00:53:36.170 --> 00:53:37.510
going up and down.

00:53:37.510 --> 00:53:39.780
And people were not
adjusting to that.

00:53:39.780 --> 00:53:40.670
One day it was 110.

00:53:40.670 --> 00:53:41.980
The next day was 80.

00:53:41.980 --> 00:53:44.669
And that's in Fahrenheit,
because I assume most of you

00:53:44.669 --> 00:53:45.710
use Fahrenheit typically.

00:53:45.710 --> 00:53:47.760
But our game is
actually in Celsius now.

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:49.690
But the idea was
that people were not

00:53:49.690 --> 00:53:51.190
adjusting to this change.

00:53:51.190 --> 00:53:52.770
And it wasn't realistic.

00:53:52.770 --> 00:53:56.620
So what we do now is we actually
ramp up the temperature,

00:53:56.620 --> 00:53:59.780
and so that the first day,
very few if any people faint.

00:53:59.780 --> 00:54:01.790
And then the next day,
by the end of day,

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:03.880
people start fainting,
because it's getting hot.

00:54:03.880 --> 00:54:05.880
And then the third day,
they're fainting faster.

00:54:05.880 --> 00:54:08.680
And you'll see that in the
playthrough after this.

00:54:08.680 --> 00:54:11.550
So during this whole process, we
made some good and bad choices.

00:54:11.550 --> 00:54:14.300
And I'd like to talk
about bad choices first.

00:54:14.300 --> 00:54:17.000
So we made two major--
these were the two,

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:19.580
I think, biggest
bad choices we made.

00:54:19.580 --> 00:54:22.160
They're not completely
horrible or anything.

00:54:22.160 --> 00:54:24.690
The first was that we
depended on external code.

00:54:24.690 --> 00:54:28.200
And the second is we focused
on education, not fun.

00:54:28.200 --> 00:54:31.140
So when I mentioned the external
code, one of our teammates

00:54:31.140 --> 00:54:33.970
had a dialogue system
for unity, which

00:54:33.970 --> 00:54:38.140
is really cool, it looked really
nice, had lot of features.

00:54:38.140 --> 00:54:39.400
And we said, let's go for it.

00:54:39.400 --> 00:54:43.000
We can use this as a foundation
to build a really complex game.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:45.320
And something we really
didn't stop to think about

00:54:45.320 --> 00:54:47.930
was how much work is it
going to be to develop

00:54:47.930 --> 00:54:49.774
our game around this system?

00:54:49.774 --> 00:54:51.940
How much work is it going
to be to change the system

00:54:51.940 --> 00:54:53.220
to fit our game?

00:54:53.220 --> 00:54:57.570
And also are we going to
have time to do all of that

00:54:57.570 --> 00:55:00.660
and also focus on making the
game complete as a whole,

00:55:00.660 --> 00:55:03.680
instead of just kind of
showcasing this one aspect.

00:55:03.680 --> 00:55:06.120
And it turns out it was a
bit of a pitfall for us,

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:09.280
because we didn't expect it to
take as much time as it did.

00:55:09.280 --> 00:55:12.150
And if we were to go back,
the teams kind of said,

00:55:12.150 --> 00:55:15.940
well, maybe we still do this
and we just deal with the issues

00:55:15.940 --> 00:55:16.440
early on.

00:55:16.440 --> 00:55:19.170
But also, maybe we should have
just designed a simpler game

00:55:19.170 --> 00:55:21.630
and not use this external code.

00:55:21.630 --> 00:55:23.270
Another bad choice
we made was we

00:55:23.270 --> 00:55:25.010
really did focus
on education, which

00:55:25.010 --> 00:55:27.920
was good, because our
game does teach people.

00:55:27.920 --> 00:55:31.210
But it is an educational
game in the sense

00:55:31.210 --> 00:55:34.120
that it's not the
most fun in the world.

00:55:34.120 --> 00:55:37.470
And if we were to
redo this, we probably

00:55:37.470 --> 00:55:39.110
should have focused
on fun earlier.

00:55:39.110 --> 00:55:41.410
We played with
having funny dialogue

00:55:41.410 --> 00:55:44.284
and making more emotionally
resonating effects.

00:55:44.284 --> 00:55:46.450
But at the end of the day,
it's an educational game.

00:55:46.450 --> 00:55:50.560
And it's really not
that exciting to play.

00:55:50.560 --> 00:55:51.910
So that's something.

00:55:51.910 --> 00:55:53.570
But in the process
of doing that,

00:55:53.570 --> 00:55:55.370
we made some good choices too.

00:55:55.370 --> 00:55:58.830
And one of those good choices
we made was group meetings.

00:55:58.830 --> 00:56:01.440
You get so much done
when you sit down

00:56:01.440 --> 00:56:04.160
with like most of your
team for three hours

00:56:04.160 --> 00:56:05.790
and you just hammer through.

00:56:05.790 --> 00:56:07.480
And we did that multiple times.

00:56:07.480 --> 00:56:09.840
And it really worked out for us.

00:56:09.840 --> 00:56:12.860
Something else we did
well was prioritize.

00:56:12.860 --> 00:56:15.120
Because we had a
team of nine people,

00:56:15.120 --> 00:56:18.570
we really had-- availability
was kind of all over the place.

00:56:18.570 --> 00:56:20.530
And even when we
had group meetings,

00:56:20.530 --> 00:56:23.570
you could only really expect
like six people to show up.

00:56:23.570 --> 00:56:25.820
You were guaranteed that at
least three people weren't

00:56:25.820 --> 00:56:27.010
going to be there.

00:56:27.010 --> 00:56:29.360
Even if you did a
doodle, which we did.

00:56:29.360 --> 00:56:32.660
So what we prioritized
was based on group--

00:56:32.660 --> 00:56:35.020
we had groups of people with
different responsibilities.

00:56:35.020 --> 00:56:39.026
But if there was a bug, we said,
OK, who is available right now?

00:56:39.026 --> 00:56:40.150
What are you're working on?

00:56:40.150 --> 00:56:41.380
Is this more of a priority?

00:56:41.380 --> 00:56:42.770
Can you do this now?

00:56:42.770 --> 00:56:44.920
And that process worked for us.

00:56:44.920 --> 00:56:47.340
We got bug after bug
fixed that way when

00:56:47.340 --> 00:56:48.809
we weren't in a group meeting.

00:56:48.809 --> 00:56:50.350
And when we got to
the group meeting,

00:56:50.350 --> 00:56:52.910
people generally had a
sense of what was going on,

00:56:52.910 --> 00:56:54.670
because we were doing
this process of they

00:56:54.670 --> 00:56:57.080
kind of had maybe worked on
something for a little bit

00:56:57.080 --> 00:56:59.370
based on it being a priority.

00:56:59.370 --> 00:57:01.730
So now, let's get
to the actual game.

00:57:01.730 --> 00:57:06.905
So the game has a start screen
within an instruction screen,

00:57:06.905 --> 00:57:08.790
which is kind of the sublayer.

00:57:08.790 --> 00:57:11.610
The main game, which has
the day scene and then

00:57:11.610 --> 00:57:14.260
a newspaper scene at the night,
and I'll show you all these.

00:57:14.260 --> 00:57:16.110
And then the end screen.

00:57:16.110 --> 00:57:18.800
So originally, this was what
our start screen looked at

00:57:18.800 --> 00:57:20.160
that we play tested.

00:57:20.160 --> 00:57:22.260
And it was beautiful,
as you can see up there.

00:57:22.260 --> 00:57:24.350
No need for changes, right?

00:57:24.350 --> 00:57:26.170
So we actually did change it.

00:57:26.170 --> 00:57:28.460
And so now, it's
the same background

00:57:28.460 --> 00:57:30.050
as a game for Cohesion.

00:57:30.050 --> 00:57:31.550
You have your play,
but you can also

00:57:31.550 --> 00:57:34.091
use the instructions, which are
pretty useful if you've never

00:57:34.091 --> 00:57:36.020
played before.

00:57:36.020 --> 00:57:38.590
And then that takes
you to our main game.

00:57:38.590 --> 00:57:40.280
Our main game
originally, you saw that

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:41.760
on the first focus test.

00:57:41.760 --> 00:57:44.820
I think this is pretty similar
to our second focus test.

00:57:44.820 --> 00:57:48.720
You see we had a progression
with the main game.

00:57:48.720 --> 00:57:50.610
It took a lot of iteration.

00:57:50.610 --> 00:57:52.600
And something originally
we didn't have,

00:57:52.600 --> 00:57:54.260
I said, was there
was no indication

00:57:54.260 --> 00:57:57.690
of when somebody was getting
sick or their characteristics.

00:57:57.690 --> 00:57:59.070
It was a lot of issues.

00:57:59.070 --> 00:58:01.620
So we made some progress.

00:58:01.620 --> 00:58:04.546
We added the indicator that
say, I'm about to faint.

00:58:04.546 --> 00:58:06.170
You should probably
try to help me now,

00:58:06.170 --> 00:58:09.160
which is that little explanation
part on part of their head.

00:58:09.160 --> 00:58:11.457
And then finally,
we redid pretty much

00:58:11.457 --> 00:58:12.290
all of the graphics.

00:58:12.290 --> 00:58:13.206
And that took a while.

00:58:13.206 --> 00:58:16.000
So we were in the process of
redoing them at this point.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:18.240
And now, the game
looks like this.

00:58:18.240 --> 00:58:19.920
So it's much more cohesive.

00:58:19.920 --> 00:58:21.230
All the art fits together.

00:58:21.230 --> 00:58:23.355
The people are really
visually caricatures

00:58:23.355 --> 00:58:26.140
of the different types of
people you need to help.

00:58:26.140 --> 00:58:28.600
Elderly people, homeless
people, drunk people

00:58:28.600 --> 00:58:30.422
are all really
vulnerable to heat waves.

00:58:30.422 --> 00:58:32.630
And then there's some
characters that actually aren't

00:58:32.630 --> 00:58:34.190
on this screen
right here but that

00:58:34.190 --> 00:58:37.420
aren't as vulnerable, like
normal, like adults aren't

00:58:37.420 --> 00:58:38.320
as vulnerable.

00:58:38.320 --> 00:58:41.761
And athletes aren't
as vulnerable.

00:58:41.761 --> 00:58:44.010
So at the end of each day,
when you play this through,

00:58:44.010 --> 00:58:45.780
and you've helped your
people, and you've given them

00:58:45.780 --> 00:58:47.270
water or set up
coolers or whatever

00:58:47.270 --> 00:58:50.466
you wanted to do for the day,
you get to a newspaper scene.

00:58:50.466 --> 00:58:52.090
And the original
newspaper scene looked

00:58:52.090 --> 00:58:53.930
like this, a lot of text.

00:58:53.930 --> 00:58:56.450
It doesn't really
help you with much.

00:58:56.450 --> 00:58:57.920
No one really
cared much about it

00:58:57.920 --> 00:58:59.770
in the first
iterations of the game,

00:58:59.770 --> 00:59:02.210
because the long-term objects
hadn't been adding yet.

00:59:02.210 --> 00:59:04.470
So it's just the umbrellas
and the water coolers.

00:59:04.470 --> 00:59:06.890
And so we changed it
to look like this.

00:59:06.890 --> 00:59:10.710
It's the same information,
just a little better organized.

00:59:10.710 --> 00:59:12.950
And the other thing that
we added in the main game,

00:59:12.950 --> 00:59:14.490
we added those
buttons that says,

00:59:14.490 --> 00:59:16.574
you can set up a water
cooler or an umbrella.

00:59:16.574 --> 00:59:17.740
And that takes your time up.

00:59:17.740 --> 00:59:20.100
So if it's cool outside,
maybe you do that.

00:59:20.100 --> 00:59:23.500
But if it's like 110
degrees in Fahrenheit, then

00:59:23.500 --> 00:59:26.140
maybe you should focus on
helping people not faint.

00:59:26.140 --> 00:59:28.280
So we had that.

00:59:28.280 --> 00:59:30.785
And then say you
finish, 20 people faint

00:59:30.785 --> 00:59:33.700
or whatever-- I think
it's 20 people faint--

00:59:33.700 --> 00:59:35.100
and you get to the end screen.

00:59:35.100 --> 00:59:39.200
And our original game,
we had no end screen.

00:59:39.200 --> 00:59:41.720
And the reason for that
was, I told you we really

00:59:41.720 --> 00:59:43.410
focused on education not fun.

00:59:43.410 --> 00:59:46.180
And we just didn't think,
part of the fun of a game

00:59:46.180 --> 00:59:48.640
is seeing how long you survive.

00:59:48.640 --> 00:59:50.500
But we just weren't
thinking about that.

00:59:50.500 --> 00:59:52.630
So we really reevaluated that.

00:59:52.630 --> 00:59:55.250
And we said, OK, we
definitely need an end screen.

00:59:55.250 --> 00:59:57.520
And we have it
looking like this.

00:59:57.520 --> 00:59:59.660
So it tells you how
long you lasted.

00:59:59.660 --> 01:00:01.860
And then you can see
the credits for what

01:00:01.860 --> 01:00:03.040
was involved in the game.

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:04.360
And you can play it again.

01:00:04.360 --> 01:00:08.152
So there's more feedback for
the user of how they did.

01:00:08.152 --> 01:00:10.560
And if we were going to
do this project again,

01:00:10.560 --> 01:00:14.280
there's two things I think
we'd do majorly differently.

01:00:14.280 --> 01:00:17.250
And the first is talking
about heat waves.

01:00:17.250 --> 01:00:20.540
Our group thought heat waves
were going to be really cool.

01:00:20.540 --> 01:00:23.100
We were like, oh, people
are fainting everywhere,

01:00:23.100 --> 01:00:26.497
and it's getting hot, and
we have to do something.

01:00:26.497 --> 01:00:28.330
And then you start
reading about heat waves.

01:00:28.330 --> 01:00:30.550
And basically, it gets hot.

01:00:30.550 --> 01:00:33.140
You tell people to go
inside or drink water.

01:00:33.140 --> 01:00:34.800
And that's about it.

01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:36.970
That's all a heat wave is.

01:00:36.970 --> 01:00:40.650
And so what we'd do differently
is really the passion aspect.

01:00:40.650 --> 01:00:42.790
If we're going to do a
game about heat waves,

01:00:42.790 --> 01:00:45.570
we depended kind of
on our passion coming

01:00:45.570 --> 01:00:47.702
from the thinking
heat waves were cool.

01:00:47.702 --> 01:00:49.160
I think we should
have focused more

01:00:49.160 --> 01:00:52.957
on having passion for the
game and then incorporating

01:00:52.957 --> 01:00:55.290
the-- well, also having the
game build around heat waves

01:00:55.290 --> 01:00:58.220
but really having a more
exciting game that we

01:00:58.220 --> 01:01:01.440
could somehow also get
that educational aspect in.

01:01:01.440 --> 01:01:04.000
What wed also do differently
is accountability.

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:05.560
I said we had nine people.

01:01:05.560 --> 01:01:08.590
Sometimes, people disappear
when you have that many people.

01:01:08.590 --> 01:01:10.930
And keeping dibs on
everything, especially when you

01:01:10.930 --> 01:01:13.960
have separate email threads,
can be a little confusing.

01:01:13.960 --> 01:01:16.269
So maybe look into
some of the tools

01:01:16.269 --> 01:01:18.810
that the other teams mentioned,
where you have multiple group

01:01:18.810 --> 01:01:20.130
chats and you can see them all.

01:01:20.130 --> 01:01:23.050
That looks really interesting.

01:01:23.050 --> 01:01:25.880
Future features, more
long-term options.

01:01:25.880 --> 01:01:28.520
I think that's one of
the things in our game

01:01:28.520 --> 01:01:31.760
that really helps with
the planning aspect is OK,

01:01:31.760 --> 01:01:34.220
do I want to be doing this,
like helping somebody now?

01:01:34.220 --> 01:01:36.730
Or do I wanting to be
installing an object now?

01:01:36.730 --> 01:01:39.570
And really, our
game kind of depends

01:01:39.570 --> 01:01:42.430
on that balance of choosing
who to help and then

01:01:42.430 --> 01:01:43.580
also what to do.

01:01:43.580 --> 01:01:45.010
Am I helping or not?

01:01:45.010 --> 01:01:46.440
So more long term options.

01:01:46.440 --> 01:01:48.694
And then something we
originally conceived

01:01:48.694 --> 01:01:50.110
was to have multiple
environments.

01:01:50.110 --> 01:01:51.910
And we didn't have
time to implement this.

01:01:51.910 --> 01:01:53.100
But in different
environments, you

01:01:53.100 --> 01:01:54.290
do slightly different things.

01:01:54.290 --> 01:01:55.660
Like if you're in
an office, you might

01:01:55.660 --> 01:01:57.993
want to install an AC unit,
which is different than what

01:01:57.993 --> 01:02:00.220
you'd do outside.

01:02:00.220 --> 01:02:02.340
So really look into
multiple environments.

01:02:02.340 --> 01:02:04.570
Different countries have
different environments,

01:02:04.570 --> 01:02:07.179
might have slightly different
strategies for what to do.

