01:15:28.730 --> 01:15:31.160
both from the
creation of the game

01:15:31.160 --> 01:15:33.982
and working as a team
sort of perspective.

01:15:33.982 --> 01:15:37.030
LAUREN: So firstly, I'll
go over the iteration

01:15:37.030 --> 01:15:38.530
was a lot better
on this project.

01:15:38.530 --> 01:15:41.320
In this class, we had a
total of four projects.

01:15:41.320 --> 01:15:44.304
The first three were
each over-- like,

01:15:44.304 --> 01:15:45.470
the first one was two weeks.

01:15:45.470 --> 01:15:46.460
Second one was two weeks.

01:15:46.460 --> 01:15:46.860
Third one was two weeks.

01:15:46.860 --> 01:15:48.427
And then this one
was eight weeks.

01:15:48.427 --> 01:15:50.260
So this time, we had a
lot more time to sort

01:15:50.260 --> 01:15:54.460
of decide what we wanted to
do, what we should try out,

01:15:54.460 --> 01:15:57.740
and get to sort of test each and
every single one of the ideas

01:15:57.740 --> 01:16:00.740
that we had, rather
than just focusing

01:16:00.740 --> 01:16:03.890
on one idea of having to do it,
because you only had two weeks.

01:16:03.890 --> 01:16:06.799
The other thing is that
after three projects,

01:16:06.799 --> 01:16:09.340
we finally figured out how to
do design meetings really well.

01:16:09.340 --> 01:16:11.821
We got them down to that they
were only like a half hour

01:16:11.821 --> 01:16:12.320
each.

01:16:12.320 --> 01:16:15.230
And when people showed up,
they were really productive.

01:16:15.230 --> 01:16:18.520
And so everyone figured
out what they wanted to do.

01:16:18.520 --> 01:16:19.970
They talked about the game.

01:16:19.970 --> 01:16:21.680
It got done, and people
got out of there.

01:16:21.680 --> 01:16:24.380
It was very nice.

01:16:24.380 --> 01:16:27.160
Another thing we did
right was simplifying.

01:16:27.160 --> 01:16:29.540
It was really hard
to adjust scope.

01:16:29.540 --> 01:16:31.067
It was easier in
the other games,

01:16:31.067 --> 01:16:32.900
because you realize you
only have two weeks.

01:16:32.900 --> 01:16:35.149
When you have eight weeks,
you think you can do a lot,

01:16:35.149 --> 01:16:36.336
and you really can't.

01:16:36.336 --> 01:16:37.710
You think you have
a lot of time,

01:16:37.710 --> 01:16:41.320
but classes and
applying to jobs,

01:16:41.320 --> 01:16:43.490
and everything takes
all of your time.

01:16:43.490 --> 01:16:45.450
And so you have to
really learn to,

01:16:45.450 --> 01:16:47.580
OK, like, I only have so
much time for this class.

01:16:47.580 --> 01:16:49.580
I can only do so
much on this game,

01:16:49.580 --> 01:16:51.340
so I'm going to
adjust the scope.

01:16:51.340 --> 01:16:55.100
And it was really hard even when
the client, when Pablo told us,

01:16:55.100 --> 01:16:57.710
you should change what you're
doing, we didn't want to.

01:16:57.710 --> 01:16:59.436
We thought, no, this
is a great idea.

01:16:59.436 --> 01:17:00.560
This is how it should work.

01:17:00.560 --> 01:17:02.490
But then when the
client tells you do it

01:17:02.490 --> 01:17:05.080
and all your play testers
say your idea is bad,

01:17:05.080 --> 01:17:08.720
you need to just
give in and change.

01:17:08.720 --> 01:17:10.820
And we ended up having
really great results.

01:17:10.820 --> 01:17:13.340
With the simpler gameplay,
it's a lot more fun.

01:17:13.340 --> 01:17:15.880
And the options, there
are less options,

01:17:15.880 --> 01:17:17.780
but they're much
more meaningful.

01:17:17.780 --> 01:17:19.350
As you could see,
the player was sort

01:17:19.350 --> 01:17:21.260
of reading through
each and every option.

01:17:21.260 --> 01:17:23.940
And it's because they each
do something different.

01:17:23.940 --> 01:17:25.900
Before, we had a
lot more options.

01:17:25.900 --> 01:17:27.980
But they were all
sort of the same.

01:17:27.980 --> 01:17:31.090
You just kind of click
them, and they do something.

01:17:31.090 --> 01:17:32.990
But they're all just
about the same effect.

01:17:32.990 --> 01:17:35.110
With this, they all
have different effects.

01:17:35.110 --> 01:17:36.800
So you sort of
have to strategize.

01:17:36.800 --> 01:17:39.100
Do I want to spend more
money for this effect?

01:17:39.100 --> 01:17:42.070
Or can I just use this cheaper
effect over and over again

01:17:42.070 --> 01:17:43.020
for the same result?

01:17:45.710 --> 01:17:48.290
STUDENT: So I'm going to
talk a little bit about what

01:17:48.290 --> 01:17:50.583
changed from beginning to end.

01:17:50.583 --> 01:17:54.920
So the UI in the beginning
looks much uglier.

01:17:54.920 --> 01:17:57.010
I mean, that just came
with sort of refining that.

01:17:57.010 --> 01:17:59.470
I want to talk a lot about
sort of the design changes

01:17:59.470 --> 01:18:00.490
that really changed.

01:18:00.490 --> 01:18:04.300
So in our first
prototype of the game,

01:18:04.300 --> 01:18:07.570
you sort of click these
buttons here on the right.

01:18:07.570 --> 01:18:10.390
And that would give
you the actions.

01:18:10.390 --> 01:18:12.140
Whereas, in the final
version of the game,

01:18:12.140 --> 01:18:14.740
you click on the villages, and
that gives you the actions.

01:18:14.740 --> 01:18:16.730
And this came from
something that Pablo

01:18:16.730 --> 01:18:19.140
told us early on and really
made a big difference, which

01:18:19.140 --> 01:18:21.970
is like people that are used
to playing video games get

01:18:21.970 --> 01:18:25.400
this concept of click
action, apply to object.

01:18:25.400 --> 01:18:28.530
But we realized, both through
play testing and again

01:18:28.530 --> 01:18:30.340
Pablo telling us,
that when you don't

01:18:30.340 --> 01:18:32.840
have that sort of experience,
working in a lot of videogames

01:18:32.840 --> 01:18:35.269
and just having that
context in your head,

01:18:35.269 --> 01:18:36.560
that doesn't really make sense.

01:18:36.560 --> 01:18:38.560
It makes much more
sense to the people

01:18:38.560 --> 01:18:42.030
that we're aiming this game
for to click on the object

01:18:42.030 --> 01:18:43.900
and then choose an action.

01:18:43.900 --> 01:18:47.090
So like that inverting
of the order of things

01:18:47.090 --> 01:18:49.600
actually makes a big
difference in helping

01:18:49.600 --> 01:18:51.510
to understand the
game and just making

01:18:51.510 --> 01:18:53.980
the whole thing smoother.

01:18:53.980 --> 01:18:57.190
On top of that, we
sort of like really

01:18:57.190 --> 01:18:59.639
refined the information
that we're showing

01:18:59.639 --> 01:19:00.680
when you look at the map.

01:19:00.680 --> 01:19:02.471
So right now, like in
the original version,

01:19:02.471 --> 01:19:04.025
you look at the
map and you sort of

01:19:04.025 --> 01:19:06.150
don't see straight away
everything you need to see.

01:19:06.150 --> 01:19:07.860
You need to go to
each of the villages

01:19:07.860 --> 01:19:09.401
individually to know
what's going on.

01:19:09.401 --> 01:19:11.770
You sort of can only see
where each village is,

01:19:11.770 --> 01:19:15.562
or where each locality is
and how much health it has.

01:19:15.562 --> 01:19:18.020
Whereas in the final version,
we sort of give you every you

01:19:18.020 --> 01:19:18.649
need to see.

01:19:18.649 --> 01:19:20.190
And it took a long
time to figure out

01:19:20.190 --> 01:19:21.356
how we wanted to do this UI.

01:19:21.356 --> 01:19:23.350
Like, how do we show
what prevention measures

01:19:23.350 --> 01:19:24.190
are in place?

01:19:24.190 --> 01:19:25.690
How do we show
whether the infection

01:19:25.690 --> 01:19:27.990
is growing or decreasing?

01:19:27.990 --> 01:19:30.230
And how do we show which
way the river is flowing?

01:19:30.230 --> 01:19:32.880
All of these questions were
really important and really led

01:19:32.880 --> 01:19:35.650
into the final design.

01:19:35.650 --> 01:19:38.650
Secondly, about like
options, at first we

01:19:38.650 --> 01:19:40.577
had lots of options, too many.

01:19:40.577 --> 01:19:42.910
People did not even want to
figure out what each of them

01:19:42.910 --> 01:19:43.390
did.

01:19:43.390 --> 01:19:45.181
It was too much
information thrown at once.

01:19:45.181 --> 01:19:47.770
And although we thought
that having lots of options

01:19:47.770 --> 01:19:49.840
would lead to meaningful--
like, oh, well,

01:19:49.840 --> 01:19:51.110
you can make these
advanced strategies.

01:19:51.110 --> 01:19:53.151
It really didn't, because
people didn't even want

01:19:53.151 --> 01:19:54.590
to bother learning all that.

01:19:54.590 --> 01:19:58.380
Whereas, in the final
version, having fewer options

01:19:58.380 --> 01:20:02.090
made it much easier or
like much less scary

01:20:02.090 --> 01:20:04.520
when you opened up the list
of options, the actions

01:20:04.520 --> 01:20:06.340
that you have available
to you as a player.

01:20:06.340 --> 01:20:08.560
And it was much more
accessible, while still

01:20:08.560 --> 01:20:12.104
making the strategies diverse.

01:20:12.104 --> 01:20:13.770
So now, we're going
to talk a little bit

01:20:13.770 --> 01:20:17.280
about what went wrong in the
process of making the game.

01:20:17.280 --> 01:20:21.400
So working together
is really hard,

01:20:21.400 --> 01:20:23.360
because people are
stepping over their toes.

01:20:23.360 --> 01:20:24.312
Oh, what do I do now.

01:20:24.312 --> 01:20:26.520
Oh, I can't touch that,
because you're touching that.

01:20:26.520 --> 01:20:28.400
Like, all these sort
of problem arise.

01:20:28.400 --> 01:20:30.850
And so at first, we really
tried to avoid that.

01:20:30.850 --> 01:20:35.010
But then we realized working
apart is even harder than that.

01:20:35.010 --> 01:20:37.030
Initially, you think,
well, if we're each

01:20:37.030 --> 01:20:39.090
working on really sort
of independent parts

01:20:39.090 --> 01:20:40.930
and we bring it all together
in the end, that'll be happy.

01:20:40.930 --> 01:20:41.620
Everyone will be happy.

01:20:41.620 --> 01:20:42.911
We're not stepping on our toes.

01:20:42.911 --> 01:20:45.820
We can each work on our own
time and that sort of thing.

01:20:45.820 --> 01:20:48.690
But that turns out not to work
well, because people do things

01:20:48.690 --> 01:20:49.362
differently.

01:20:49.362 --> 01:20:51.070
People follow-- like,
even simple things,

01:20:51.070 --> 01:20:53.600
like coding style and how
you name your variables

01:20:53.600 --> 01:20:55.700
and all that sort of
stuff makes a difference.

01:20:55.700 --> 01:20:57.560
And if you're not
working together closely,

01:20:57.560 --> 01:20:59.410
and if you sort of
working apart, bringing

01:20:59.410 --> 01:21:02.067
that together was a
huge hassle at the end.

01:21:02.067 --> 01:21:04.400
Like we spent a lot of time
just making sure everything,

01:21:04.400 --> 01:21:06.483
all the components that
we had made as individuals

01:21:06.483 --> 01:21:09.074
worked together, just
to get the game running.

01:21:09.074 --> 01:21:10.740
LAUREN: So another
thing that went wrong

01:21:10.740 --> 01:21:12.900
was the motivation
for this project.

01:21:12.900 --> 01:21:15.020
At the very beginning,
the team wasn't

01:21:15.020 --> 01:21:17.370
very passionate about the
project to begin with,

01:21:17.370 --> 01:21:18.689
which is really hard.

01:21:18.689 --> 01:21:20.230
It's really hard to
work on something

01:21:20.230 --> 01:21:22.716
that you don't really
love and want to do.

01:21:22.716 --> 01:21:25.090
And I thought, you know, maybe
this will just get better.

01:21:25.090 --> 01:21:27.310
People will start to have ideas.

01:21:27.310 --> 01:21:29.060
They'll feel ownership
of the project.

01:21:29.060 --> 01:21:31.490
And then they'll be more
motivated to work on it.

01:21:31.490 --> 01:21:33.190
But that's not true.

01:21:33.190 --> 01:21:35.600
People, if they start
off in a bad place,

01:21:35.600 --> 01:21:37.100
they're not going
to get any better.

01:21:37.100 --> 01:21:40.520
You really have to focus
on somehow helping people

01:21:40.520 --> 01:21:43.990
to either learn to
love the project

01:21:43.990 --> 01:21:48.230
or learn to just be
able to work on it.

01:21:48.230 --> 01:21:50.770
And this can be done
through different ways.

01:21:50.770 --> 01:21:52.320
The easiest way is
just to get people

01:21:52.320 --> 01:21:54.320
to realize like we
have to do this,

01:21:54.320 --> 01:21:56.560
so you have to work on it.

01:21:56.560 --> 01:21:59.690
And I found it as-- towards
the end of the semester,

01:21:59.690 --> 01:22:01.300
it took me to
figure this one out.

01:22:01.300 --> 01:22:03.350
But if you give people
vague instructions,

01:22:03.350 --> 01:22:06.010
they will wait until
the very last second.

01:22:06.010 --> 01:22:07.810
But if you make
it crystal clear,

01:22:07.810 --> 01:22:10.560
exactly what you want
them to do and give

01:22:10.560 --> 01:22:12.950
them is as detailed
instructions you can,

01:22:12.950 --> 01:22:16.490
it's much more likely that it'll
get done in a timely manner.

01:22:16.490 --> 01:22:19.100
And also, we felt
really restricted

01:22:19.100 --> 01:22:21.600
by the topic and
the requirements,

01:22:21.600 --> 01:22:25.160
which was another just
problem in motivation.

01:22:25.160 --> 01:22:28.680
And so crunch is something
I was sort of alluding to,

01:22:28.680 --> 01:22:30.860
is that when you
have the instructions

01:22:30.860 --> 01:22:33.560
and you don't want to do
something, you will put it off.

01:22:33.560 --> 01:22:34.190
I do it.

01:22:34.190 --> 01:22:38.259
I am sure everyone else does it
that I don't want to do this.

01:22:38.259 --> 01:22:40.050
I don't understand what
they want me to do,

01:22:40.050 --> 01:22:42.820
so I'm just going to wait
until the last possible second

01:22:42.820 --> 01:22:45.230
when I have to do it
or I'm going to fail.

01:22:45.230 --> 01:22:47.190
And that's when it
gets done, which

01:22:47.190 --> 01:22:49.770
is what I think was a
leading thing to our crunch.

01:22:49.770 --> 01:22:51.280
And so we had
constant crunching.

01:22:51.280 --> 01:22:53.160
Every time we knew
we had to play test,

01:22:53.160 --> 01:22:55.950
the night before,
everyone was up working.

01:22:55.950 --> 01:22:59.675
And there was a huge
crunch after Thanksgiving.

01:22:59.675 --> 01:23:01.550
We took until Thanksgiving,
and then everyone

01:23:01.550 --> 01:23:04.605
realized we don't have that much
for longer in this semester.

01:23:04.605 --> 01:23:06.230
We only have like a
week and three days

01:23:06.230 --> 01:23:08.090
before this final presentation.

01:23:08.090 --> 01:23:10.660
So there was a lot
of crunch there.

01:23:10.660 --> 01:23:13.070
And the work was low priority
because of other classes,

01:23:13.070 --> 01:23:16.190
which is a really unique problem
to doing a school project, as

01:23:16.190 --> 01:23:18.720
opposed to doing a
project in the real world,

01:23:18.720 --> 01:23:21.060
where people still might
have other things to do,

01:23:21.060 --> 01:23:22.272
but this is their job.

01:23:22.272 --> 01:23:24.230
Whereas, when this is a
class, you can't really

01:23:24.230 --> 01:23:25.525
fire someone from your class.

01:23:28.447 --> 01:23:30.530
Let's see, you want to
talk about what we learned?

01:23:30.530 --> 01:23:31.880
STUDENT: Yeah.

01:23:31.880 --> 01:23:35.406
So what we learned in terms of
game design, at least for me

01:23:35.406 --> 01:23:38.030
and probably for everyone on the
team, what was most surprising

01:23:38.030 --> 01:23:40.930
is that giving more choices and
making a game more complicated

01:23:40.930 --> 01:23:42.310
does not make it more fun.

01:23:42.310 --> 01:23:43.940
Initially I thought,
more choices

01:23:43.940 --> 01:23:46.900
means more strategic
diversity or whatever,

01:23:46.900 --> 01:23:48.700
and that'll make
everything more exciting.

01:23:48.700 --> 01:23:49.600
And every time
you play the game,

01:23:49.600 --> 01:23:50.610
you can try something different.

01:23:50.610 --> 01:23:51.980
But that's not really true.

01:23:51.980 --> 01:23:54.730
Having less choices
can be even more

01:23:54.730 --> 01:23:56.647
fun than having more
choices, because then you

01:23:56.647 --> 01:23:58.563
don't have-- like when
the player doesn't have

01:23:58.563 --> 01:24:00.220
to think about as
much at once, they

01:24:00.220 --> 01:24:03.480
can really go deeper into
what the current options are.

01:24:03.480 --> 01:24:06.150
So that was really surprising.

01:24:06.150 --> 01:24:09.380
Also in terms of game design,
requirements can be restrictive

01:24:09.380 --> 01:24:13.570
and often you can't do
what you want to do.

01:24:13.570 --> 01:24:15.602
You as a designer can't
do what you want to do,

01:24:15.602 --> 01:24:18.060
can't fulfill your own fantasy
for what the game is opposed

01:24:18.060 --> 01:24:19.880
to look like, because
of the requirements,

01:24:19.880 --> 01:24:21.650
because of what clients want,
and because of what players

01:24:21.650 --> 01:24:22.240
want.

01:24:22.240 --> 01:24:25.560
And you have to learn to
sort of deal with that.

01:24:25.560 --> 01:24:27.220
The designer is
not always right.

01:24:27.220 --> 01:24:29.594
Just because I have an idea
for what the game is supposed

01:24:29.594 --> 01:24:31.360
to look like, if I
test on 10 people

01:24:31.360 --> 01:24:33.520
and all 10 people
say I don't like it,

01:24:33.520 --> 01:24:36.550
I'd prefer it to be this
way, then I'm wrong.

01:24:36.550 --> 01:24:37.484
I have to change that.

01:24:37.484 --> 01:24:39.400
And that's something
that's hard to deal with,

01:24:39.400 --> 01:24:41.191
but it's something you
have to learn to do.

01:24:43.150 --> 01:24:46.600
Yeah, we learned a
lot about cholera.

01:24:46.600 --> 01:24:49.270
Basically, as we said
in one of first slides,

01:24:49.270 --> 01:24:52.030
washing hands is
overpowered in real life.

01:24:52.030 --> 01:24:54.634
If you just wash-- very simple
things can prevent cholera.

01:24:54.634 --> 01:24:57.050
And that's something we wanted
to get across in this game.

01:24:57.050 --> 01:24:59.430
In the game, washing hands
is overpowered, just so

01:24:59.430 --> 01:25:01.690
that they get that idea across.

01:25:01.690 --> 01:25:04.524
And about coding, there's
a lot of simple things

01:25:04.524 --> 01:25:06.190
you can do to really
polish up the game,

01:25:06.190 --> 01:25:09.100
like tweening, which is a
animation API available,

01:25:09.100 --> 01:25:10.610
and Phaser that we used.

01:25:10.610 --> 01:25:13.480
But really any animation API
that does like little things,

01:25:13.480 --> 01:25:15.410
like having the window
pop up instead of just

01:25:15.410 --> 01:25:19.270
appear, having things go like
"paching!" and move in and out,

01:25:19.270 --> 01:25:21.894
that makes a huge difference
for very little effort.

01:25:21.894 --> 01:25:23.810
And it makes the game
look much more polished.

01:25:27.780 --> 01:25:30.770
In terms of future changes
for the game itself,

01:25:30.770 --> 01:25:33.734
we initially planned to
have seasons and lots

01:25:33.734 --> 01:25:36.400
of random events that would sort
of make the game more exciting,

01:25:36.400 --> 01:25:38.650
especially near the end,
once all four villages are up

01:25:38.650 --> 01:25:41.020
and you sort of get
into this pattern.

01:25:41.020 --> 01:25:45.160
But we basically didn't
have time to do that.

01:25:45.160 --> 01:25:47.740
And then the second thing that
at least I personally wanted

01:25:47.740 --> 01:25:50.180
to add to the game was more
advanced infection models.

01:25:50.180 --> 01:25:52.566
It turns out that modeling
infection is-- well,

01:25:52.566 --> 01:25:53.690
it's not surprising really.

01:25:53.690 --> 01:25:55.400
But modeling infection
is really hard.

01:25:55.400 --> 01:25:56.910
Balancing your
model of infection

01:25:56.910 --> 01:25:58.550
is really, really hard.

01:25:58.550 --> 01:26:01.560
And it's sort of
almost impossible

01:26:01.560 --> 01:26:03.590
to make it have this
sort of smooth curve,

01:26:03.590 --> 01:26:05.280
where it starts out
easy and then gets

01:26:05.280 --> 01:26:07.760
sort of hard at the
end but not too hard.

01:26:07.760 --> 01:26:10.260
Infection is
exponential in nature.

01:26:10.260 --> 01:26:11.940
And that's really
hard to deal with.

01:26:11.940 --> 01:26:13.324
If I had more time
to work on it,

01:26:13.324 --> 01:26:14.740
I'd probably spend
a lot more time

01:26:14.740 --> 01:26:17.110
thinking about different
models to use for infection

01:26:17.110 --> 01:26:18.560
and make it easier to balance.

01:26:18.560 --> 01:26:20.850
Like right now, you change
like one little number

01:26:20.850 --> 01:26:22.560
by hardly anything,
and the game goes

01:26:22.560 --> 01:26:25.600
from really, really easy
to completely impossible,

01:26:25.600 --> 01:26:28.884
just because of the
nature of infection.

