01:29:51.993 --> 01:29:54.060
LIZ RITA: We're the
Saving Gora Gora team.

01:29:54.060 --> 01:29:57.035
I'm Liz, Rachel, Kevin, Justin.

01:29:57.035 --> 01:29:58.410
There are others
in the audience.

01:30:01.315 --> 01:30:03.800
Go to the beginning.

01:30:03.800 --> 01:30:04.840
Yeah.

01:30:04.840 --> 01:30:11.240
So to start us off, I'm going
to talk about, let's see,

01:30:11.240 --> 01:30:15.730
the goals that we had
from the beginning.

01:30:15.730 --> 01:30:18.310
Our product is about cholera
and cholera prevention.

01:30:18.310 --> 01:30:21.060
And our audience was
Ghanaian children.

01:30:21.060 --> 01:30:25.890
So we had to find a way to
connect Ghanaian children

01:30:25.890 --> 01:30:27.820
to this information
about cholera

01:30:27.820 --> 01:30:32.140
prevention, positive behaviors,
proactive things they can

01:30:32.140 --> 01:30:34.480
do in the community, while
also having a fun game

01:30:34.480 --> 01:30:37.220
that they can relate to.

01:30:37.220 --> 01:30:39.486
What this ultimately
meant is that we

01:30:39.486 --> 01:30:41.110
had to do a lot of
research, because we

01:30:41.110 --> 01:30:44.190
didn't have a direct
connection with our audience.

01:30:44.190 --> 01:30:46.190
And we couldn't
directly play test

01:30:46.190 --> 01:30:49.840
with children from
Ghana, ages 8 to 13.

01:30:49.840 --> 01:30:53.500
We had to make a lot of
assumptions, which ended up

01:30:53.500 --> 01:30:57.000
being wrong after we talked to
Pablo, specifically about them.

01:30:57.000 --> 01:30:58.310
So we did some more research.

01:30:58.310 --> 01:31:02.820
We looked at Ghana,
cartoons targeted

01:31:02.820 --> 01:31:04.330
towards children in Ghana.

01:31:04.330 --> 01:31:09.850
And from those cartoons, we
looked at the color palettes,

01:31:09.850 --> 01:31:13.350
some behaviors within
the cartoon specifically,

01:31:13.350 --> 01:31:17.830
and names and sort of character
designs from the cartoons.

01:31:17.830 --> 01:31:22.960
And we got Ghana research
from documentaries and stuff,

01:31:22.960 --> 01:31:27.880
also informed decisions that
we used to change minigames,

01:31:27.880 --> 01:31:31.170
which we'll talk about
later in the presentation.

01:31:31.170 --> 01:31:35.186
A quick overview of the
narrative-- you start the game.

01:31:35.186 --> 01:31:36.810
There is this monster
hiding in a bush.

01:31:36.810 --> 01:31:38.070
You go to check him out.

01:31:38.070 --> 01:31:41.590
It turns out that
he's being persecuted,

01:31:41.590 --> 01:31:44.500
because everybody in
Gora Gora is sick.

01:31:44.500 --> 01:31:46.030
And they think he's the cause.

01:31:46.030 --> 01:31:49.200
And Sal is actually a cool guy.

01:31:49.200 --> 01:31:51.350
You're a bunny, and
your name is Kojo,

01:31:51.350 --> 01:31:53.500
and you're a cool guy, too.

01:31:53.500 --> 01:31:56.250
So you're asked to prove
that he's innocent.

01:31:56.250 --> 01:32:01.170
And you take that up, because
you're an awesome person.

01:32:01.170 --> 01:32:03.500
The gameplay ends
up being that you

01:32:03.500 --> 01:32:07.140
explore the town,
looking for ways

01:32:07.140 --> 01:32:09.400
to prove that Sal is innocent.

01:32:09.400 --> 01:32:12.170
And you do that by
unlocking these minigames

01:32:12.170 --> 01:32:13.810
and getting clues
from the minigames

01:32:13.810 --> 01:32:15.680
after you defeat the minigames.

01:32:15.680 --> 01:32:18.110
And after each minigame, you
can go talk to the mayor,

01:32:18.110 --> 01:32:21.667
or you have the choice to,
because he has an office.

01:32:21.667 --> 01:32:23.500
And when you have all
the clues, you finally

01:32:23.500 --> 01:32:28.356
convince the mayor that Sal
is harmless, which is great.

01:32:28.356 --> 01:32:30.890
KEVIN WANG: So
our first minigame

01:32:30.890 --> 01:32:32.560
dealt with water filtration.

01:32:32.560 --> 01:32:36.190
And the concept behind it is
that friends and neighbors

01:32:36.190 --> 01:32:39.850
are bringing containers
of water to Kojo's mom.

01:32:39.850 --> 01:32:42.380
And they want to see whether
the water is safe to drink,

01:32:42.380 --> 01:32:45.650
or whether they have to purify
it beforehand by boiling.

01:32:48.540 --> 01:32:51.520
So that, and when we
initially designed our game,

01:32:51.520 --> 01:32:56.330
it turned out to be water
filtration kind of factoring,

01:32:56.330 --> 01:32:59.590
in which bottles of water were
going down a conveyor belt.

01:32:59.590 --> 01:33:03.120
And you were asked to remove
the bottles that were unpurified

01:33:03.120 --> 01:33:06.290
and that needed to be cleaned.

01:33:06.290 --> 01:33:10.980
So as you see on the left, that
was our very first iteration.

01:33:10.980 --> 01:33:14.480
And I guess the issue with
that, as Pablo brought up to us,

01:33:14.480 --> 01:33:17.030
was that it wasn't
relatable to the kids

01:33:17.030 --> 01:33:19.800
that we were trying to target,
because these kids likely

01:33:19.800 --> 01:33:23.879
won't ever see a facility that
has these conveyor belts, that

01:33:23.879 --> 01:33:25.170
does this kind of purification.

01:33:25.170 --> 01:33:28.510
So we had to go through
several iterations

01:33:28.510 --> 01:33:32.260
to figure out a way to make
the game a lot more relatable.

01:33:32.260 --> 01:33:36.260
And our final product is on the
left-- or on the right, sorry.

01:33:36.260 --> 01:33:38.190
And as you can see,
it's outside one

01:33:38.190 --> 01:33:39.890
of the homes in the village.

01:33:39.890 --> 01:33:44.330
And your mom is just standing
behind a pot of boiling water.

01:33:44.330 --> 01:33:50.020
And now, you just have plain
containers, bowls, buckets,

01:33:50.020 --> 01:33:51.160
tanks.

01:33:51.160 --> 01:33:54.750
And your goal is to kind of see
where the water is coming from,

01:33:54.750 --> 01:33:58.500
how warm it is, and try
to figure out whether you

01:33:58.500 --> 01:34:01.380
want to boil it or not.

01:34:01.380 --> 01:34:06.040
So some challenges we faced
were, in our first iteration,

01:34:06.040 --> 01:34:07.760
it was more of a
real time game play.

01:34:07.760 --> 01:34:10.120
You were kind of rushing
against time to pull off

01:34:10.120 --> 01:34:14.470
all the unfiltered water,
as all the bottles continued

01:34:14.470 --> 01:34:16.120
to scroll to the
right, regardless

01:34:16.120 --> 01:34:17.844
of how fast you were going.

01:34:17.844 --> 01:34:19.510
But then we realized
that took away kind

01:34:19.510 --> 01:34:22.700
of from the educational aspect,
because it forced the player

01:34:22.700 --> 01:34:27.290
to just kind of hurriedly just
pull everything that they can.

01:34:27.290 --> 01:34:30.410
So instead, we changed
it to a styled gameplay

01:34:30.410 --> 01:34:33.820
that was kind of at
the player's pace.

01:34:33.820 --> 01:34:37.130
They can do everything as
fast or as slow as they want.

01:34:37.130 --> 01:34:40.400
And that, I think, gives
the player a better chance

01:34:40.400 --> 01:34:42.700
to kind of learn
everything there

01:34:42.700 --> 01:34:44.215
is to learn from the minigame.

01:34:47.228 --> 01:34:51.480
RACHEL WANG: Cool, so the second
minigame is a water collection

01:34:51.480 --> 01:34:54.650
game, where you're asked to help
your friend [? Korku ?] find

01:34:54.650 --> 01:34:56.830
where to collect water from.

01:34:56.830 --> 01:34:58.581
And so with this
development process,

01:34:58.581 --> 01:35:00.080
it was kind of
similar to what Kevin

01:35:00.080 --> 01:35:03.680
was saying about making it,
like have as high of a learning

01:35:03.680 --> 01:35:05.610
value as possible.

01:35:05.610 --> 01:35:08.940
And then another aspect of this
game was making it fail-safe.

01:35:08.940 --> 01:35:11.100
So obviously, we thought
there was one right answer

01:35:11.100 --> 01:35:13.940
that the player should
take away from it.

01:35:13.940 --> 01:35:16.290
But we didn't want
them to fail and then

01:35:16.290 --> 01:35:19.030
not win the game at the end,
if they were to not choose

01:35:19.030 --> 01:35:20.450
the right location.

01:35:20.450 --> 01:35:23.070
So one way we dealt
with that was,

01:35:23.070 --> 01:35:26.300
every time the player chose
a wrong location, there'd

01:35:26.300 --> 01:35:29.060
be immediate feedback,
saying, oh, this

01:35:29.060 --> 01:35:32.750
isn't such a good place to
collect water from because.

01:35:32.750 --> 01:35:34.580
And so as you can
see, this example

01:35:34.580 --> 01:35:36.580
is, if you were to collect
water from the river,

01:35:36.580 --> 01:35:39.110
you don't know if there's
excreta from upstream

01:35:39.110 --> 01:35:42.250
or if someone's peeing
in the river right now.

01:35:42.250 --> 01:35:46.060
So then it'll ask you
to try another place.

01:35:46.060 --> 01:35:48.140
We also did a feature
cut pretty early on,

01:35:48.140 --> 01:35:50.940
which was also finding someone
to dispose of your excreta.

01:35:50.940 --> 01:35:54.880
And so we focused on the
water, which would hopefully

01:35:54.880 --> 01:35:57.460
focus the player's
attention in figuring out

01:35:57.460 --> 01:36:00.890
where to place water and really
think about the water aspect

01:36:00.890 --> 01:36:04.700
and not so much as another
aspect of the game.

01:36:04.700 --> 01:36:07.541
So the other challenge
was, as Liz and Kevin

01:36:07.541 --> 01:36:10.040
already pointed out, was there's
a huge cultural difference.

01:36:10.040 --> 01:36:13.630
So again, I have like a
before and after shot of what

01:36:13.630 --> 01:36:15.110
our landscape looked like.

01:36:15.110 --> 01:36:17.810
And so originally, there
was snow-capped mountains,

01:36:17.810 --> 01:36:18.810
a lot of grass.

01:36:18.810 --> 01:36:21.390
But from our research, we
saw that this didn't really

01:36:21.390 --> 01:36:23.410
look like Ghana landscape.

01:36:23.410 --> 01:36:25.160
We had a water
treatment facility,

01:36:25.160 --> 01:36:28.710
which originally was the correct
place to collect water from.

01:36:28.710 --> 01:36:31.470
But we eventually changed
that to be a well.

01:36:31.470 --> 01:36:35.110
And so that's more
realistic in terms of where

01:36:35.110 --> 01:36:36.780
people collect water in Ghana.

01:36:36.780 --> 01:36:40.310
Additionally, at the
end there is a task bar,

01:36:40.310 --> 01:36:42.430
so it provides
you more feedback.

01:36:42.430 --> 01:36:44.020
If you clicked on
any of the buildings

01:36:44.020 --> 01:36:46.950
it'll provide you feedback
about what that place is,

01:36:46.950 --> 01:36:49.132
and whether or not you
should or shouldn't

01:36:49.132 --> 01:36:50.506
be placing water there.

