So the premise of this game
is that the doctor in the town

01:37:07.680 --> 01:37:08.280
is very busy.

01:37:08.280 --> 01:37:09.988
He can't go out into
the town to actually

01:37:09.988 --> 01:37:12.300
check on patients to see
if they're seeing any

01:37:12.300 --> 01:37:13.910
of the early signs of cholera.

01:37:13.910 --> 01:37:17.170
So he asks you to help him
by going out and talking

01:37:17.170 --> 01:37:19.690
to some of your friends in
town, and then asking them

01:37:19.690 --> 01:37:21.430
if they're having
any of the symptoms,

01:37:21.430 --> 01:37:23.221
and then ask them to
come in to the doctor.

01:37:25.510 --> 01:37:27.689
We initially started
off by having

01:37:27.689 --> 01:37:30.230
this game be a game where you
help the doctor in the doctor's

01:37:30.230 --> 01:37:30.774
office.

01:37:30.774 --> 01:37:32.440
And he's diagnosing
patients, and you're

01:37:32.440 --> 01:37:34.360
sort of diagnosing
the patients with him.

01:37:34.360 --> 01:37:35.984
And we realized that
this would quickly

01:37:35.984 --> 01:37:37.820
turn into sort of a
quiz-type of game,

01:37:37.820 --> 01:37:40.284
and it would really detract
from the learning aspect.

01:37:40.284 --> 01:37:42.825
It would essentially the same
as just reading the systems out

01:37:42.825 --> 01:37:43.980
of a pamphlet.

01:37:43.980 --> 01:37:47.010
So we decided that by adding
more interactivity by forcing

01:37:47.010 --> 01:37:49.070
the player to go
out into the village

01:37:49.070 --> 01:37:51.200
and actually find
people and talk to them

01:37:51.200 --> 01:37:53.770
and then ask them to
come to the clinic

01:37:53.770 --> 01:37:56.080
would be a lot more engaging,
while still maintaining

01:37:56.080 --> 01:37:58.870
the same educational aspect
about trying to search

01:37:58.870 --> 01:38:00.790
for the right symptoms.

01:38:00.790 --> 01:38:04.240
Additionally, we
made a change where

01:38:04.240 --> 01:38:07.880
we had the player go talk to
some of the villagers that

01:38:07.880 --> 01:38:08.940
were adults.

01:38:08.940 --> 01:38:12.160
And then we realized that--
after speaking with Pablo,

01:38:12.160 --> 01:38:13.930
that the social
hierarchy in Ghana

01:38:13.930 --> 01:38:16.680
is not necessarily that
of the United States.

01:38:16.680 --> 01:38:19.360
And this sort of
interaction, where

01:38:19.360 --> 01:38:21.730
a child asks something or
sort of demands something

01:38:21.730 --> 01:38:23.280
of an adult, isn't
really something

01:38:23.280 --> 01:38:25.470
that would happen, just
because of the stricter

01:38:25.470 --> 01:38:26.230
social hierarchy.

01:38:26.230 --> 01:38:28.660
So we decided that it'd
be more appropriate if we

01:38:28.660 --> 01:38:31.140
had the child go talk
to some of his friends

01:38:31.140 --> 01:38:32.460
that were of the same age.

01:38:32.460 --> 01:38:34.362
And then tell
them, since they're

01:38:34.362 --> 01:38:37.970
on the same sort of level,
to go to the doctor's office,

01:38:37.970 --> 01:38:40.734
rather than talking to elders.

01:38:40.734 --> 01:38:42.150
Some of the
challenges that we saw

01:38:42.150 --> 01:38:45.520
were that this game is
heavily dialogue-based.

01:38:45.520 --> 01:38:50.460
It's almost entirely interacting
through our dialogue UI.

01:38:50.460 --> 01:38:53.290
And so we needed to do a lot
of iteration on that in order

01:38:53.290 --> 01:38:55.720
to make sure that it was
clear who was speaking

01:38:55.720 --> 01:38:59.422
and give the appropriate choices
so that the player can make

01:38:59.422 --> 01:39:01.760
meaningful decisions while
having his interactions

01:39:01.760 --> 01:39:03.000
with the villagers.

01:39:03.000 --> 01:39:05.410
And finally, since it
is so dialogue-heavy,

01:39:05.410 --> 01:39:08.026
there's a problem that comes
when making a game for children

01:39:08.026 --> 01:39:10.150
when you have a lot of
text, because they might not

01:39:10.150 --> 01:39:11.440
be the strongest reader.

01:39:11.440 --> 01:39:13.170
So we focused w
lot on making sure

01:39:13.170 --> 01:39:15.280
that the vocabulary
was simple, and we

01:39:15.280 --> 01:39:17.505
tried to keep the sentence
structure as simple

01:39:17.505 --> 01:39:18.990
as possible, and
straightforward,

01:39:18.990 --> 01:39:20.630
to get the message
across to children.

01:39:23.780 --> 01:39:25.330
So some of the
overall challenges

01:39:25.330 --> 01:39:27.450
that we faced while doing
the game development

01:39:27.450 --> 01:39:29.740
was mastering the
states with Phaser.

01:39:29.740 --> 01:39:31.940
This is sort of an intricacy
of the Phaser engine

01:39:31.940 --> 01:39:35.530
itself, where when you spawn
off the different stages

01:39:35.530 --> 01:39:38.310
of the map, making sure
that we can maintain

01:39:38.310 --> 01:39:41.400
the data across all
these different states,

01:39:41.400 --> 01:39:44.650
so that there can be a sort
of progress through the game.

01:39:44.650 --> 01:39:47.330
And finally, we want to make
sure that the game wasn't

01:39:47.330 --> 01:39:50.480
too difficult. For example,
with the facility game

01:39:50.480 --> 01:39:53.000
at the beginning when we had
the very fast-paced clicking,

01:39:53.000 --> 01:39:54.833
and then you would fail
almost all the time.

01:39:54.833 --> 01:39:57.140
We wanted to make sure that
it wasn't too difficult,

01:39:57.140 --> 01:39:59.374
and that it was accessible.

01:39:59.374 --> 01:40:01.040
The cultural disconnect
we touched a bit

01:40:01.040 --> 01:40:03.260
on in some of our
previous games,

01:40:03.260 --> 01:40:06.000
making sure that the
target audience will

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:07.890
be able to play this
game and relate to it

01:40:07.890 --> 01:40:10.050
in order to pull
the message from it,

01:40:10.050 --> 01:40:11.500
and making the play meaningful.

01:40:11.500 --> 01:40:14.640
We wanted to make sure that
the game play was still

01:40:14.640 --> 01:40:16.950
getting the message across,
and finding a good balance

01:40:16.950 --> 01:40:20.148
between education and play.

01:40:20.148 --> 01:40:21.620
RACHEL WANG: So
now I'll talk about

01:40:21.620 --> 01:40:23.410
how our teamwork
worked out, and what

01:40:23.410 --> 01:40:25.130
our process like as a team.

01:40:25.130 --> 01:40:27.290
So we used four main tools.

01:40:27.290 --> 01:40:30.370
The first one being Trello,
to keep track of our tasks

01:40:30.370 --> 01:40:31.100
and progresses.

01:40:31.100 --> 01:40:34.270
So, we'd put all our sprint
task lists, our product backlog,

01:40:34.270 --> 01:40:35.275
on to the Trello.

01:40:35.275 --> 01:40:36.900
People would claim
the different tasks,

01:40:36.900 --> 01:40:39.050
and then be able to say
if they were doing them,

01:40:39.050 --> 01:40:41.340
if they were done, or
if they haven't started.

01:40:41.340 --> 01:40:43.050
And then that means
we could track

01:40:43.050 --> 01:40:45.670
how people's progress was.

01:40:45.670 --> 01:40:47.200
The second one was
weekly meetings.

01:40:47.200 --> 01:40:49.560
So, every week we had
a meeting to either do

01:40:49.560 --> 01:40:52.710
some research about Ghana,
talk about how we could improve

01:40:52.710 --> 01:40:54.820
the game play and make
it more meaningful,

01:40:54.820 --> 01:40:57.140
if we should cut some
features, and whatnot.

01:40:57.140 --> 01:41:00.740
So, these meetings were really
great for quick and efficient

01:41:00.740 --> 01:41:03.590
decisions, and also really
important decisions.

01:41:03.590 --> 01:41:06.755
Our third tool was Slack, which
some other teams talked about.

01:41:06.755 --> 01:41:10.470
But it was really great because,
first, they had Google Drive

01:41:10.470 --> 01:41:13.590
integration, so you could see
when people were pushing code

01:41:13.590 --> 01:41:15.417
if you should be pulling code.

01:41:15.417 --> 01:41:17.750
And then, in addition, we
could have different channels.

01:41:17.750 --> 01:41:20.170
So we had a separate
coding channel,

01:41:20.170 --> 01:41:23.510
where all the coders
could talk to each other,

01:41:23.510 --> 01:41:26.000
and that might not be
relevant to other people.

01:41:26.000 --> 01:41:27.960
And then having a
whole team channel

01:41:27.960 --> 01:41:29.460
was also efficient,
because it would

01:41:29.460 --> 01:41:32.374
be faster response than email.

01:41:32.374 --> 01:41:34.040
And then our final
one was Google Drive,

01:41:34.040 --> 01:41:36.180
which is where we
have all our assets,

01:41:36.180 --> 01:41:38.406
had all our dialogues,
our characters.

01:41:38.406 --> 01:41:40.280
And this worked out to
be a really great tool

01:41:40.280 --> 01:41:43.830
for collaborative storage.

01:41:43.830 --> 01:41:46.770
Some downfalls of
this was-- I'll

01:41:46.770 --> 01:41:50.874
talk about the second
part, was basically

01:41:50.874 --> 01:41:53.290
with all these tools you need
to make sure that everyone's

01:41:53.290 --> 01:41:54.390
actually using the tools.

01:41:54.390 --> 01:41:56.860
It's not actually effective
to be using Trello

01:41:56.860 --> 01:41:58.455
if not everyone's using Trello.

01:41:58.455 --> 01:41:59.840
And we found this
to be the case,

01:41:59.840 --> 01:42:02.340
not everyone would be updating
their progress on Trello,

01:42:02.340 --> 01:42:04.460
or not everyone
would be on Slack .

01:42:04.460 --> 01:42:05.950
But some mitigations
we had to that

01:42:05.950 --> 01:42:08.180
is, in like Slack, you can
mention people's names,

01:42:08.180 --> 01:42:09.555
and then it'll
send them an email

01:42:09.555 --> 01:42:13.330
if they're not actually
on Slack at that time.

01:42:13.330 --> 01:42:15.920
We did have to remind people
to be updating the Trello board

01:42:15.920 --> 01:42:18.970
or updating their progress
in Slack, or just ping

01:42:18.970 --> 01:42:20.880
people individually in email.

01:42:20.880 --> 01:42:23.002
But I think we worked it out.

01:42:23.002 --> 01:42:24.460
Something we could
have improved on

01:42:24.460 --> 01:42:27.900
was enforcing deadlines,
and having deadlines.

01:42:27.900 --> 01:42:31.550
As Kevin will talk about, we had
different roles between coding

01:42:31.550 --> 01:42:32.770
and art designing.

01:42:32.770 --> 01:42:35.370
So, obviously the
art assets had to be

01:42:35.370 --> 01:42:38.020
done before you could really
code things and put it

01:42:38.020 --> 01:42:39.000
into the game.

01:42:39.000 --> 01:42:42.170
So in that aspect, we
should have probably

01:42:42.170 --> 01:42:44.830
had clearer deadlines
so that we could

01:42:44.830 --> 01:42:47.950
stick to a stricter schedule.

01:42:47.950 --> 01:42:50.610
And then, in addition,
we should have probably

01:42:50.610 --> 01:42:53.250
had a bit more
frequent communication

01:42:53.250 --> 01:42:54.520
with the entire team.

01:42:54.520 --> 01:42:56.220
So we did have a lot
of communication,

01:42:56.220 --> 01:42:58.840
but sometimes not all the
team members were present,

01:42:58.840 --> 01:43:01.390
and we should have
probably improved

01:43:01.390 --> 01:43:03.610
a bit about sending
out meeting notes

01:43:03.610 --> 01:43:06.140
and catching up people who
weren't at the meetings

01:43:06.140 --> 01:43:08.860
when we made certain decisions.

01:43:08.860 --> 01:43:11.780
And to that regard,
something that we could just

01:43:11.780 --> 01:43:14.730
do for next time is,
send out meeting notes,

01:43:14.730 --> 01:43:16.990
and keep everyone up
to date, and possibly

01:43:16.990 --> 01:43:21.060
even have smaller meetings
where not everyone is present.

01:43:21.060 --> 01:43:22.990
So I guess in terms of
what went right, Kevin

01:43:22.990 --> 01:43:23.940
will talk about that.

01:43:23.940 --> 01:43:25.900
KEVIN WANG: So, as
Rachel was saying,

01:43:25.900 --> 01:43:29.380
we separated a lot of the tasks
of the project between the team

01:43:29.380 --> 01:43:29.880
members.

01:43:29.880 --> 01:43:33.740
And since we had
seven people, we

01:43:33.740 --> 01:43:36.970
designated four to coding,
two to design and art,

01:43:36.970 --> 01:43:38.950
and then a few others
to the other aspects

01:43:38.950 --> 01:43:43.010
such as narrative, project
management, and sound.

01:43:43.010 --> 01:43:45.230
So, that actually
helped us a lot,

01:43:45.230 --> 01:43:49.010
in that having only four
coders rather than seven really

01:43:49.010 --> 01:43:52.540
cut down on the number of
merge conflicts and issues

01:43:52.540 --> 01:43:55.590
that we had in
previous projects.

01:43:55.590 --> 01:43:57.220
Because, obviously,
the fewer number

01:43:57.220 --> 01:44:00.010
of people working on each
file, the less likely

01:44:00.010 --> 01:44:01.885
it's all going to
break when people merge

01:44:01.885 --> 01:44:04.216
their stuff together in GitHub.

01:44:04.216 --> 01:44:05.840
And with the art
designers, it actually

01:44:05.840 --> 01:44:07.260
helped to have just two.

01:44:07.260 --> 01:44:10.150
Because, although they
had to do more work,

01:44:10.150 --> 01:44:12.570
it was easier for them to
collaborate and make sure

01:44:12.570 --> 01:44:15.810
that all of their art followed
the same theme, rather than

01:44:15.810 --> 01:44:17.880
coming from three or four
different sources that

01:44:17.880 --> 01:44:19.790
look slightly different.

01:44:19.790 --> 01:44:23.050
Eduardo and Liz were very
capable in making sure

01:44:23.050 --> 01:44:26.150
that all the art had the
same kind of color palate,

01:44:26.150 --> 01:44:27.700
and the same kind
of cultural theme

01:44:27.700 --> 01:44:32.070
to it, which helped, I think,
unify our game in the end.

01:44:32.070 --> 01:44:36.260
And, as Rachel also said, we had
semi-frequent meetings, mostly

01:44:36.260 --> 01:44:38.780
at the end of the weeks,
just to catch up and see

01:44:38.780 --> 01:44:41.040
how everybody was
doing on their parts,

01:44:41.040 --> 01:44:44.240
and what we were planning
on doing for the next week.

01:44:44.240 --> 01:44:46.320
And it also served
as a good time for us

01:44:46.320 --> 01:44:48.130
to really sit down and
get some work done,

01:44:48.130 --> 01:44:52.850
whether it's drawing some new
assets, coding a new minigame.

01:44:52.850 --> 01:44:56.110
And having most of the people
there together at the same time

01:44:56.110 --> 01:44:58.420
allowed us to really
bounce ideas off each other

01:44:58.420 --> 01:45:00.480
when we were implementing
this, which made

01:45:00.480 --> 01:45:02.110
things a lot more efficient.

01:45:02.110 --> 01:45:06.400
And lastly, we realize
that at the beginning,

01:45:06.400 --> 01:45:09.930
we had probably more
than we could take on

01:45:09.930 --> 01:45:11.390
over this eight-week period.

01:45:11.390 --> 01:45:14.910
So we did a good job of
cutting features early.

01:45:14.910 --> 01:45:17.440
And the main one we did was
cutting the fourth minigame out

01:45:17.440 --> 01:45:20.510
of our game entirely,
so that we could really

01:45:20.510 --> 01:45:22.920
focus on making the three
minigames that we have

01:45:22.920 --> 01:45:28.029
currently really robust and
really relevant to the ideas

01:45:28.029 --> 01:45:29.070
we were trying to convey.

01:45:31.662 --> 01:45:35.490
RACHEL WANG: So moving forward
from this where hopefully we

01:45:35.490 --> 01:45:38.270
would be able to find more
of our target audience,

01:45:38.270 --> 01:45:39.925
our focus tests helped
a lot whether it

01:45:39.925 --> 01:45:43.550
was speaking to Pablo, other MIT
students, people in the class.

01:45:43.550 --> 01:45:45.960
They gave us a lot of good
feedback about the game.

01:45:45.960 --> 01:45:48.670
But obviously we
didn't get a chance

01:45:48.670 --> 01:45:52.520
to speak with Ghanaian kids,
which is our target audience.

01:45:52.520 --> 01:45:55.830
And that could definitely
help if we had a longer period

01:45:55.830 --> 01:46:00.130
and were able to find
even kids ages 8 to 13.

01:46:00.130 --> 01:46:03.020
In terms of iteration,
I think we could still

01:46:03.020 --> 01:46:05.670
focus a bit more on
balancing the difficulty.

01:46:05.670 --> 01:46:08.130
And then we mitigated
that by doing things

01:46:08.130 --> 01:46:13.330
like what Justin said about
changing the text dialogue,

01:46:13.330 --> 01:46:16.460
and also providing a lot of
help tutorials or instructions

01:46:16.460 --> 01:46:17.439
throughout the game.

01:46:17.439 --> 01:46:19.480
But that's something we
could always think about,

01:46:19.480 --> 01:46:22.390
so that even kids younger
than our target audience

01:46:22.390 --> 01:46:24.650
could access the game.

01:46:24.650 --> 01:46:26.480
And then, obviously,
just making sure

01:46:26.480 --> 01:46:30.000
the game is culturally relevant,
thinking about word choices,

01:46:30.000 --> 01:46:35.530
thinking about assets, something
we could always improve on.

01:46:35.530 --> 01:46:38.370
And then, finally, to actually
keep moving forward we

01:46:38.370 --> 01:46:40.170
could implement
another minigame,

01:46:40.170 --> 01:46:42.010
find out other
things about cholera

01:46:42.010 --> 01:46:44.620
we really want to get across,
and add other adventures

01:46:44.620 --> 01:46:46.040
to the game.

01:46:46.040 --> 01:46:50.290
But the game right now is
pretty contained, and gives,

01:46:50.290 --> 01:46:52.850
we think, three valuable
lessons about cholera,

01:46:52.850 --> 01:46:55.360
and three very concrete
preventative actions

01:46:55.360 --> 01:46:57.520
that you can take,
and bring back

01:46:57.520 --> 01:47:00.579
to your village and your family.

01:47:00.579 --> 01:47:02.370
So I guess that's what
we would think about

01:47:02.370 --> 01:47:03.620
if we were going to go for it.

01:47:03.620 --> 01:47:07.819
And now, we'll
move into our demo.

01:47:07.819 --> 01:47:09.360
So, I guess, if
there's any questions

01:47:09.360 --> 01:47:14.945
first we can take those, or else
we'll be looking for a demo-er.

